deck_name: Masters 1 Guide to PUNK Gold Pride (January 2024)
deck_excerpt: Gold Pride is finally out on Masterduel! Outrace your opponents all the way to Masters 1!
deck_description:
"Gold Pride" seems to be tailor made specifically to play with PUNK. Not only are the cards aesthetically similar, both archetypes reward the duelist for paying/losing lifepoints - allowing them to draw cards, special summon combo pieces, and power up their boss monsters (10300ATK Psychic End Punisher anyone?)! The inherent synergy is immense since PUNK naturally combos into Gold Pride and the lifepoint payments by PUNK allow all Gold Pride monsters to special summon themselves for free!
 
The deck's end board from only one Ze Amin + 1 discard is composed of 3 pops (Start Your Engines, Star Leon and PUNK Nashiwari Surprise), non-targeting/destroying monster removal (Pin Baller) and 3 cards draw (PUNK Jam Session and Better Luck Next Time!). Not only that, but follow-up for the grind game is also generated by the constant summons of Captain Carrie, searching your starter "Start Your Engines" during your turn and your opponent's turn! If allowed to combo off, this deck ends with a full board, and a 6 card hand full of hand traps/follow-up. This deck also is infamous for easily bringing out Psychic End Punisher, a "towers" monster that most decks are unprepared to deal with. 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
In contrast to other duelist's iterations of this deck, my personal PUNK Gold Pride list is big, consisting of 50 cards! It is 50 cards since one Ze Amin + discard is full combo, and there are 15 copies of Ze Amin (3 Ze Amin, 3 Ogre, 3 Foxy Tune, 3 Emergency Teleport and 3 Small World) giving the duelist a fair chance of drawing into it with their starting hand. 50 cards also make it less likely that you will hard draw your garnets (Sharakusai, Deer Note, Wa Gon and Jam Session) that are essential for the combo. Trust me, 50 cards is still surprisingly consistent and totally not bricky!
 
The two archetypes in this deck are of course Gold Pride (12 cards) and PUNK (15 cards). PUNK cards are your starters for the main combo while Gold Pride are extenders that your board generally ends on. Including Small World and Emergency Teleport, this deck has 14 ways to Ze Amin which is full combo. 
 
Many handtraps are included, meaning that going second, you still have a decent chance of stopping your opponent since your starting hand probably contains 1-2 handtraps. Going first, you have a great chance of drawing into them, since the PUNK + Gold Pride combo draws you three cards. Handtraps are also Small World bridges to search Ze Amin (to start your combo). In games 2-3, these handtraps are exchanged for the going-second cards in your side deck. PUNK Gold Pride can somewhat play through some interruption because it has a ridiculous amount of extenders (every Gold Pride monster summons itself for free!), but the strategy can be significantly easier to play if the board state is equalized, that's why many handtraps are used in this deck. 
 
In the Extra Deck, there is sadly no reliable way this deck can make level 10 Synchros anymore with the limit of Psy-Frame Gamma, so Baronne and Stardust Assault Synchron are replaced by a Zeus package of Fortune Tune + Downerd Magician. Knightmare Phoenix, Knightmare Unicorn and Accesscode are included in case your opponent activates Dimension Barrier against you, locking out Synchros. You can still OTK easily with links instead, since this strategy swarms the board very easily with plenty of material. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of PUNK Gold Pride is to destroy/remove your opponent's cards while building as much resource advantage as it can with multiple draws and searches. True to the "racing vs. your opponent" theme of the deck, PUNK Gold Pride's win condition is building up as much momentum as possible (card advantage and board presence). The more momentum you have, the more unstoppable are! 
 
The combo for this strategy is the standard PUNK combo -> Gold Pride combo. Here is the main combo for PUNK Gold Pride: 
 
Ze Amin + Discard = Draw 3 cards, set PUNK trap, set Start your Engines!, Leon's quick synchro (either destroy 1 monster or bounce 4), Roller Baller's monster removal
  1. (The following is standard PUNK combo) Summon Ze Amin. Ze Amin searches for Foxy Tune. 
  2. Foxy Tune effect to discard 1 card in hand to summon Sharakusai from deck. 
  3. Sharakusai fusion summons Rising Carp, using Sharakusai + Ze Amin. 
  4. Tribute Rising Carp to summon Deer Note and Wa Gon from deck. 
  5. Activate Wa Gon's effect to search for Jam Session from deck. 
  6. Activate Jam Session. 
  7. Synchro summon Dragon Drive using Wa Gon + Deer Note. 
  8. CL1 Dragon Drive to search for Madame Spider from deck, CL2 Deer Note to summon Sharakusai from GY. 
  9. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card. 
  10. Special summon Madam Spider from hand. Madame Spider searches for PUNK trap from deck. 
  11. Jam Session's trigger effect draws you 1 card a second time. 
  12. (The following is the Gold Pride combo) XYZ summon Chariot Carrie using Sharakusai + Madame Spider. 
  13. Detach 1 material from Chariot Carrie to add from deck to hand Better Luck Next Time! and send to GY Roller Baller. 
  14. Activate Better Luck Next Time to add Captain Carrie from deck. 
  15. Special summon Captain Carrie. Captain Carrie searches Start Your Engines! from deck.
  16. Set your spells/traps in your backrow. In addition to the PUNK Trap and Start your Engines! you searched, you may have additional Imperms, Crossouts and Called By, etc. to set as backrow. Summon extenders if you want, and if possible summon boss monsters like Psychic End Punisher and Dragite in your EMZ, since you needs your main monster zones free for your Gold Pride monsters. 
  17. Proceed to End Phase. Chariot Carrie activates to summon Captain Carrie from deck. This triggers Better Luck Next Time! to draw 1 card.
  18. During your opponent's turn, Activate Start your Engines! to summon Leon from deck. Leon summons from GY Roller Baller. 
With only 1 Ze Amin + discard, you get many interruptions and resources! 
 
Leon can quick synchro to destroy a monster on the field with Star Leon. Alternatively, Leon can quick synchro with Dragon Drive on board to bounce 4 cards with Amazing Dragon. Roller Baller can quick fusion to equip monsters your opponent controls. Your set Start your Engines! pops a monster. Your set PUNK trap also either negates/destroys. You also likely have many handtraps in hand. You have 4 guaranteed interruptions, probably 1-3+ handtraps, and follow-up for next turn! That's about 5-7 interruptions for your opponent to contend with, and you have more than enough resources to OTK your opponent next turn. 
 
If you're interrupted mid-combo, your plan B is to summon Psychic End Punisher to stall for next turn's counterattack, since most decks cannot out it easily. 
 
Going second, hopefully your handtraps simplify the gamestate enough to the point your in-engine combo and extenders are enough to allow you to play the game through your opponent's interruption. 
 
The PUNK Gold Pride pilot has a plethora of options to clear the board and OTK going second based on the gamestate: 
 
 A 4 material Zeus is easily summoned with 2 level 3s -> Fortune Tune -> Battle Phase attack -> Zeus. Gold Pride Star Leon and Pin Baller clear the boards of monsters while Captain Carrie's effect in the GY turn them into 4000+ ATK beatsticks. PUNK Gold Pride also easily turbos out Psychic End Punisher, a nigh unstoppable "towers" monster capable of a 1 shot kill that many decks are unprepared to face. Amazing Dragon synchro summoned with Rising Carp and Ze Amin clears 2-4 cards from the board while enabling it to attack twice with 3600ATK (7200DMG). Finally, Accesscode is available to OTK as well since this deck swarms the field very easily with lots of link material. Accesscode is a good alternative in case you get D-barrier locked from Synchros. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If you get hit by Maxx "C," Droll & Lockbird or Dimension Shifter, your plan B synchro summon Psychic End Punisher. Chances are that your opponent cannot out this monster and you'll be alive next turn to continue counterattack without committing too much of your resources. 
  • PUNK Gold Pride has an in-engine way to hardcounter the current strongest meta deck! Vs. Kashtira, make summoning Nytro Head a priority. The token it generates on your opponent's board during their Standby Phase makes plays very awkward for Kashtira, if not outright shutting down their entire strategy. 
  • Keep close track of your dangerously low lifepoints and keep your monsters in defense position unless you know you can attack for game! If you're not careful, Masquerade the Blazing Dragon's 600 lifepoint tax, Sky Striker Ace Hayate's direct attack, or Swordsoul Longyuan's 1200 damage burn can quickly end your duel. 
  • This deck's endboard folds to common board wipes like Evenly Matched and Raigeki, since it has no easy way to negate spells and traps (the limit of Psyframe Gamma makes this deck's S/T negate Baronne, difficult to make). If you feel like your opponent will attempt to boardwipe you, end your board with Psychic End Punisher so you can at least have board presence that can shrug off these high impact cards. If you're allowed full combo, you also likely have 3-6 cards in hand with many of them handtraps, so if you get boardwiped it's not the end of the duel for you. 
  • If you're feeling truly brave, a 60 card version of the deck is possible by including the card Dark Spirit's Mastery into the deck. Not only does it search Ogre Dance (which in turn searching Ze Amin), but it also searches Lava Golem, a potent board breaker! With Dark Spirit's Mastery, you have a consistent PUNK deck despite having the maximum 60 cards, since it has 17 copies of Ze Amin. 
  • Not only does Small World search Ze Amin to start your combo, it also searches incredible board breakers such as Kurikara and Lava Golem (Feel free to include these guys in your deck). From my experience nobody really negates Small World since they'd rather negate a choke point in a combo, so Small World is a great card to open with so you can start clearing your opponent's board. 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Based on the racing anime movie "Redline," Gold Pride simulates the great lengths racers in the movie go through to get a lead over their opponents by paying life points for its plays. Just like the racers in the movie lived on the edge of life and death during dangerous racing, it is the same with YOU, the duelist who gets rewarded the lower your lifepoints are! If you play this deck, you MUST watch the movie Redline to learn where these cards came from - it'll make you appreciate the deck even more!
 
The fact that it synergizes so well with another favourite strategy of mine - PUNKS, makes my heart so happy since I really appreciate the Cyberpunk aesthetic both archetypes portray. The handtrap heavy, momentum based gameplay is the style of Yugioh I personally find fun, and PUNK Gold Pride is a perfect deck for that. I feel like an absolute badass ending on a board with a ton of disruptions (no negates so my opponent can actually play) and having a full hand with handtraps/follow-up for next turn!
 
TURN UP YOUR SPEED TO THE MAXIMUM AND OUTRACE YOUR OPPONENTS!
 
GLHF Duelists!

Nouvelles - January 2024
This is a mock deck, where you can check alternatives you can use in your Treasure Panda deck, if you lack SR/UR materials.

I like Winged Kuriboh aesthetically, but I find its evolved forms to be pretty bad for all things considered. Winged Kuriboh LV10 has to be Special Summoned by Transcendent Wings which is basically a neg-3 by itself, and even once you get LV10 out, it is still a Battle Phase-oriented monster like almost, if not, all other Kuriboh monsters. Winged Kuriboh LV6 is very cute, but at the same time, it has a miserable effect. Sure, it can be searched off of Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage and have its Summoning requirement easily fulfilled in a HERO Deck, but at the same time, its effect to pop a monster on field and inflict damage really isn't all that useful considering the other things you are able to do in HERO. And then we get to the monster that we are looking at today: Winged Kuriboh LV9. It is a Level 9 LIGHT Fairy Monster that can be Special Summoned from hand using its activated effect which can only be activated as Chain Link 3 or higher. While it is on field, Spell Cards that have been activated are banished instead of being sent to GY and its ATK/DEF become equal to the number of Spells in your opponent's GY x500. Like I never read the Yu-Gi-Oh! GX manga (I've only read the Arc-V manga which is hella wierd), but I don't know if this is the exact effect that it had in the manga, and I surely cannot even imagine what situation would call for a monster like this whose effect goes against its literal ATK/DEF gaining ability. If its ATK/DEF is determined by the number of Spells in your opponent's GY, why does it banish them instead of sending them to the GY? When we put LV9 into the context of Prediction Princess, we have another issue: It is a Fairy monster which means that you cannot target it with World Legacy Monstrosity to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from the Deck because it, too, is a Fairy. Kuriboh as an archetype has some pretty fun and unique cards to support themselves, but we can't really make use of them as we are trying to specifically make use of Winged Kuriboh LV9 here, and the only cards that have anything to do with Winged Kuriboh are Sabatiel - The Philosopher's Stone, Berserker Crush, The Flute of Summoning Kuriboh, and Transcendent Wings. Berserker Crush and Transcendentn Wings are immediately out since they do things we do not need to focus on, and while Flute of Summoning Kuriboh is really nice as a theoretical way to extend, we need Level 9's in this Deck, not access to a Level 1. That leaves us with Sabatiel which is actually pretty nice in this Deck. If you have a Winged Kuriboh monster on field or in GY,  you can pay half your LP to add a Polymerization or Fusion Spell from Deck to hand similar to Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, and you've seen how I have been using Cobra to get us to Instant Fusion to access Master of Ham who can get us Bibliomuse from the Deck. That is pretty much the only upside to this Deck. I would've tossed Winged Kuriboh LV9 alongside Sacred Arch-Airknight Parshath if it wasn't for Sabatiel and the theoretical chance that you could search for Instant Fusion with the help of Winged Kuriboh. I'm not telling you to play this Deck. It really is pretty lackluster considering that the only upside is being able to search for Instant Fusion sometimes. The combo that worked for me is Diviner of the Herald, Winged Kuriboh LV9, and World Legacy Monstrosity. Normal Summon Diviner and use its effect to send Trias Hierarchia from Deck to GY. Activate Trias Hierarchia to Tribute Diviner and Summon itself from GY. Diviner triggers upon being Tributed as Chain Link 1. Chain Link 2 World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Hierarchia. Chain Link 3 Winged Kuriboh LV9 from hand. Winged Kuriboh Special Summons itself from hand. Monstrosity Special Summons Deus-X Krawler and Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag from Deck. Diviner Special Summons Winged Kuriboh from Deck. There are a couple of things you can do here. If you want to protect yourself from handtraps potentially at this point, you can Xyz Hierarchia and Winged Kuriboh LV9 into Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton who will act as a monster negate, and you can keep it on field going into your opponent's turn for a monster negate on their turn as well. Or, you can Xyz that Hierarchia and Winged Kuriboh LV9 into Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows for an interruption on your opponent's turn. But let's say you make Hyperyton here. Now Xyz Deus-X and Kaku into Merelogic Aggregator, sending Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY, search, reattach to Aggregator, then we Link Aggregator and Winged Kuriboh into I:P Masquerena, and Herald triggers again for another search. Prediction Princess shenanigans, you know the deal. Can't really do much if you don't have a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell already in your opening hand or if you drew Bibliomuse, but do what you can. We are playing Pre-Preparation of Rites to make up for it. And if you activate a Spell, you can attach it from GY to Hyperyton to give it the chance to negate a Spell. Deck is aight. Not great. Don't play this. There are plenty of other better Prediction Princess versions you can look at. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Trias Hierarchia which is a Level 9 that can Tribute a Fairy to Special Summon itself from hand or GY. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which is a Level 9 we can easily Summon from hand and it can also be Special Summoned from Deck with Monstrosity. 3 Winged Kuriboh LV9. 1 Winged Kuriboh. 3 Diviner of the Herald which can send a Fairy monster from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon and increase its Level by the Level of the sent monster. And if it is Tributed, you can Special Summon a Level 2 or lower Fairy monster from hand or Deck except for itself.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which specifically Ritual Summons Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster from Deck. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 3 Sabatiel - The Philosopher's Stone. If you have a Winged Kuriboh monster on field or in GY, you can pay half your LP to add a Polymerization or Fusion Spell from Deck to hand and if it is in GY, you can banish 3 copies of it from GY and target a monster on the field to have it gain ATK equal to the ATK of the monster on field with the highest ATK until the end fo the turn. You are not really going to be using that second effect, but it will be really funny if you manage to pull it off in some fashion. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons 1 Level 9 monster from your hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. And finally, 3 Small World.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Chaos Angel which you can make since Winged Kuriboh is a Level 1 LIGHT monster. You can treat a LIGHT or DARK monster you control as a Tuner for its Summon and if it is Special Summoned, you can target a card on field and banish it. If it used a LIGHT monster as Synchro Material, Synchros you control are unaffected by your opponent's activated monster effects and if you used a DARK monster as Synchro Material, monsters you control cannot be destroyed by battle. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, 1 Gravity Controller, and 1 Linkuriboh. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Cosmic Cyclone, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Dominant with the Dominion of the Dogmatika Nation and Constantinian Shift the Meta Game
deck_description:
"Heed our cry oh yonder nexus as we do thy word. Allow us to don thy power, as we don thy brand and grant us favor against evil"

The dogmatikamatrix is real. PRAY. Lest may ye fools face the white plague Alba Zoa and become it’s tribute

- The 3 cards  of this sect you want to start with are Nadir Servant and/or Dogmatikamatrix, with any other 2 cards. Activate Nadir Servant send Garura, Wings of Resonant Life and add Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous to hand. Activate the effect of Garura in the GY to add draw 1 card. 

Now unlike a lot of decks Ritual Dogmatika Combo relies on what cards you have in your opening hand. Although you have many cards that can "search" and add 1 or sometimes even 2 cards from deck to hand like Ecclesia, Nadir, Dogmatikamatrix and Pre-Preparation of Rites. All which at 3 copies in this deck for a total 12 searchers. The power level of your board going first or second Depends on the scenario, skill and understanding of the player.

Here's where go from here 

-  After activitng the effect of Garura, Normal Summon Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous add Dogmatikamatrix. Activate Dogmatikamatrix and add 1 Dogmatika Ritual Monster or Dogmatika Ritual Spell to your hand, and if your opponent controls a monster you can 1 addtional Dogmatika card in this case we'll add White Knight of Dogmatika. 

- Now we will assume we've opened well, and that the other card 2 card we have in our hand are Dogmatikalamity and Dogmatika Maximus. Banish Garura to summon Dogmatika Maximus and activiate Maximus's effect. Both player will then send 2 cards from the Extra Deck to the GY. Send Herald of Arc Light and El Shaddoll Apkallone, Activate the effect of both Herald of Arc Light and El Shaddoll Apkallone to add Ohime the Manifested Mikanko and Shaddoll Schism, then discard 1 other card.

- Activate Dogmatikalamity to Ritual Summon White Knight of Dogmatika sending from deck to the GY Titaniklad the Ash Dragon. Using the other effect of Dogmatikalamity on field you can send 1 card from your or your opponents Extra Deck. In this case we'll send from our Extra a deck another copy of Herald of Arc Light since the GY effect is not once per turn, we'll activate the effect to add White Relic of Dogmatika. Now we'll activate the effect of Ohime the Manifested Mikanko and add The Great Mikanko Ceremony to hand then send White Relic of Dogmatika to the GY.

- Next activate The Great Mikanko Ceremony to Special Summon Ohime the Manifested Mikanko. Activate the GY effect of The Great Mikanko Ceremony to send Mikanko Reflection Rondo to the GY. Set Shaddoll Schism and go to the End Phase, in the end phase activate the effect of Titaniklad the Ash Dragon which adds 1 Dogmatika from deck to hand the turn it is sent to the GY.  Add Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted and pass turn.

Here's another line

- The 2 cards of this sect you want this time is Dogmatikamatrix, Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous and a Dogmatikalamity. Activate Dogmatikamatrix and add 1 White Relic of Dogmatika if you have Dogmatikamacabre or Dogmatika Alba Zoa if you have Dogmatikalamity. Normal Summon Ecclesia and search which ever Ritual Monster you didn't add to hand. In this case we'll Ritual Summon Relic using Dogmatikamacabre sending Ecclesia to the GY.  Activate the on field effect of Dogmatikamatrix to send Herald of Arc Light to the GY and add which ever ritual spell you didn't have, in this case we'll add Dogmatikalamity from deck to hand and Then activate it to Ritual Summon Dogmatika Alba Zoa sending Despian Luluwalilith. 

- Activate the effect of Alba Zoa and since they have no monsters that can be return to the Extra Deck the first effect cannot be applied and since the effect has to resolve your opponent will be forced to choose the 2nd effect of Alba Zoa making them Send 7 card from their hand and/or Extra Deck to the GY. And While Relic is on the field your level 8 or higher Dogmatika monster cannot be destoryed by battle make Alba Zoa pretty hard to out.

Notes and Tips*

- In the second line if you summon Dogmatika Alba Zoa First you can activate the on summon effect of White Relic of Dogmatika and target Alba Zoa and have White Relic of Dogmatika's atk become 4000!

- Dogmatika Alba Zoa other field effect makes so that "Dogmatika" monsters you control are unaffected by the activated effects of your opponent's Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and Link Monsters and it has 4000 atk!...But other than that it has no other protection from card effects like Raigkei so keep that in mind 

- If your you can't get to main line combo try to make you opponent burn through as much interuption as possible and make a "low impact" Play like sending Despian Luluwalilith from Extra Deck something like Dogmatikalamity and during the end activate her to Special Summon Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous and add to hand Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted using Ecclesia on summon effect.

Abyss Actors are fun, here are some lines:

Abyss Actors' Dress Rehearsal (6004133) - Activate Dress Rehearsal at the start of your m1. Add Abyss Scrip - Dramatic Story and Abyss Actor - Wild Hope. Normal summon Wild Hope and activate Dramatic Story. Summon from the deck Abyss Actor - Superstar and destroy Wild Hope to add to your hand Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser. Link Summon into Abyss Actor - Hyper Director. Put in your pendulum scale Curtain and then summon it with Hyper Director putting in the pendulum zone Abyss Actor - Mellow Madonna. Use Curtain effect to send Abyss Script - Opening Ceremony and then add to your hand back the Superstar. Link summon into Abyss Actor - Super Producer and then with Madonna add from your deck to your hand Abyss Actor - Liberty Dramatist. Go for a pendulum summon with Madonna and Dramatist and summon out all of your monsters (Superstar, Wild Hope and Curtain). Activate the effect of Superstar and set your Abyss Script - Abysstainment. Activate Abysstainment and tribute Curtain to set Ceremony from graveyard. Then use the effect of Super Producer to pop Abysstainment to activate Abyss Playhouse - Fantastic Theatre. Now you have a draw 5 and you still play tons of handtraps.

Abyss Actor - Curtain Raiser (44179224) and Abyss Actors' Dress Rehearsal (6004133) - activate Rehearsal to add Wild Hope and Dramatic Story. Activate Curtain Raiser and then use it's effect to summon it. Normal Summon Wild Hope and then use Dramatic Story to pop it and summon Superstar. Effect of Wild Hope will add you Superstar. With Raiser send Ceremony to grave to add back Wild Hope. Activate Superstar and tribute of a Superstar to add back Dramatic Story. Use Raiser to link summon into Hyper Producer and use his effect to summon Superstar and put in pend zone Madonna. Link summon into Super Producer. Madonna will add you Liberty Dramatist and now pendulum summon your Wild Hope from hand and 2 Superstar from extra deck. Activate Superstar and set Abysstainment and with it tribute Superstar to set Ceremony. Destroy Abysstainment for effect of Super Producer to activate Playhouse. Now you have a draw 5 into handtraps and a bounce 2.

Those are just starter combos, of course depending on your hand this deck can go into Apolloussa with 3 and Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon with a draw 5, it can go into S:P set-up with Masquerena with draw 5 and Vortex, it can do a lot of things which also includes a board wipe that cannot be responded to. Good Luck Fellow Duelists!

A fun combo deck I've been messing around with inspired by a Jesse Kotton video. Still working on the ratios, but so far this has worked the best for me. This is by no means a super competitive build and there are some big choke points in the full combo, but there are some back up options if you're stopped. I'm also not a competitive player, just a casual on ladder. Also the deck is expensive and is not budget friendly.

Card Explanations:

Prisma/A Hero Lives (AHL)/E-Call: Heart and soul of the deck. This is your combo starter. You always want to see Prisma or a way into it. AHL is ideal, but normal summoning it works fine, it's just riskier. 

Souls Package (Souls/IOC/Prep): I use three of each for this because you always want to see some way into souls for full combo w/ Prisma. If you don't you can still end on Sprind, Schism, Granguignol, and a token, but you don't get the double bounce with Sprind/Sargas or the omni from Regulus. Illusion of Chaos shuffle back into the deck comes up quite often for cards you don't want to draw (O-Lion, Regulus, Schism). This package also works pretty well as hand trap bait. If you're going second, you can make Anima with Souls and potentially steal a card if you are trying to break a board, but feel free to cut Anima if you'd like to try something else. 

Scareclaw/Starfrost Package: Your combo engine. Gets you into Cross-Sheep, Proxy F Magician, and Astraloud. You can also always fall back into a Baronne and grab Twinsaw in certain situations. (See combo below)

Cartesia/Granguignol/Luluwalilith: Cartesia is your second Prisma target. Make Granguignol w/ 2nd Prisma + Souls to send Apkellone and add Schism. You can cheat Luluwalilith out with Granguignol on your opponents turn to get an extra monster negate. Also if you have Cartesia + any way into Souls but no Prisma, you can still get into Granguignol for a Winda play. *Note: You will have to detach Granguignol from Sargas if you XYZ'd before you can summon Lulu.*

Shaddoll Package/Selene: Here to make Winda on your opponents turn. You will normally use this to make your Sprind/Sargas bounces live on Winda summon, so be careful not to use this right away if you can avoid it. Winda summon can also make your Lulu negate live on summon if there is a target for it. Winda also works well as a material for Selene on follow up who can summon back any Spellcaster (Granguignol/Souls/Cartesia) and then link into Accesscode. If you get to Accesscode you should probably be OTK'ing as you'll have 5300 ATK and 4 Links in grave to use for its effect.

Sprind/Sargas/Regulus/O-Lion: Sargas adds you Regulus while Sprind sends O-lion to GY. This gives you an omninegate on top of Sprind detaching a material from Sargas to bounce, which in turn activates Sargas to bounce/destroy another card. 

ROTA: Extra search for Prisma or Reicheart.

Hand Traps: Ash is usually a must in MasterDuel as we all know, but I have left out Maxx C (if Konami is reading this, BAN MAXX C) since the deck is 45 cards already, feel free to add this if you'd like. I have yet to mess with a 60 card version of this deck because the deck relies highly on a consistent 2-card combo, but may try it for extra non-engine. Veiler is a must in my opinion as it can be used as a normal summon to make Granguignol if you don't see Souls and have AHL to still make full combo. Imperm is here to dodge Triple Tac/Thrust. I've contemplated adding Droll here as well due to Mannadium/Superheavy. Called by the Grave is must for the occasional Ash/Maxx C negate. You could also add Crossout, but I felt it was not at full potential without Maxx C or Droll. 

This deck wants to go 1st. Some effects, such as Astraloud's can be used when going 2nd, but I have skipped those in the below combo.

Full Combo: Special summon Souls> Normal summon Prisma > send Visas to GY> make Lightheart> add/activate Planet> add/summon Reicheart > add Arrival > make Cross Sheep > activate Arrival > summon Visas > activate Lightheart GY effect > summon Light heart > make Proxy F > Special Astraloud by banishing Visas/Reicheart > Cross Sheep effect to summon back Prisma. *Note: It is important to make Cross Sheep BEFORE using Arrival as most of the time if you have summoned Souls, Cross Sheep will be your 5th summon. Holding Arrival allows you to play through Nibiru, however it won't be full combo.*

Second half of combo: use 2nd Prisma effect > send Cartesia to GY > activate Proxy F effect to fuse > make Granguignol (with Souls & Prisma) > send Apkellone to GY > add Schism > overlay Granguignol and Astraloud for Sargas > make Sprind w/ Sheep & Proxy F > send O-Lion to GY w/ Sprind effect > add Regulus by Sargas effect > special summon Regulus using O-lion in the GY. *Note: The O-lion token is not necessary for any part of the combo so feel free to skip its summon, but keeping it in defense w/ Planet on the field can give you an extra pop on follow up. Also feel free to use Souls effect before fusing it off to send Planet to the GY for a draw. This can sometimes net you an added Hand Trap, but you lose out on the follow up pop.*

Your endboard should look like this: Sprind (Bounce), Sargas (Bounce/Destroy), Schism (>Winda (SS floodgate)), Regulus (Omni), & a token. You should also have Granguignol's effect to summon Lulu (monster negate) once you've detached from Sargas for his effect. Also, ALWAYS PLAY YOUR MONSTERS IN DEFENSE ON TURN 1 EXCEPT WINDA. Winda is the exception because you don't want your opponent to just run her over with their normal summon. This will protect you from board wipes and will make your Planet live at the start of your next turn. 

On followup: If your board is relatively unscathed at the end of your opponents turn, you can simply link into Selene w/ Sprind+Winda, bring back a Spellcaster w/ Selene's effect, and link into Accesscode for game. *Note: you should usually make Selene w/ Winda or Winda's effect will stop you from making Accesscode! Also Winda can only attack other monsters, so she is no good anyway if you're attacking for game unless there is a monster on your opponents field. 

Other Techs: This combo can end on a plethora of other things as well, so experiment as you like. I've used Draglubion + Heart Earth (w/ Barian Shark attached) to rank up into Ultimate Falcon, Desavewurm (GY) + Avramax + Hope Harbinger, Sprind + Hope Harbinger, and a more Branded heavy package in different builds of the deck and I'm sure there are other ways it could combo forever, but there are only so many ED spaces. I also cut a small Dogmatika package to reduce bricking, but Ecclesia could theoretically be added off of Lulu if your opponent outs it or summoned off of Granguignol instead of Lulu, which in turn would add you Fleur de Lis. This felt a bit unnecessary to me, but it's there if you want it. 

Overall the deck is relatively fragile yet fun and doesn't necessarily FTK, but gets pretty close. Hope you enjoy!

Allure of Darkness

The purpose of this deck is to banish as many cards you can and hit hard by using Gren Maju Da Eiza . You can do this with the Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher  quick effect, which allows you to summon itself from hand or graveyard by banishing 8 cards. If you accidentally banish all green maju cards, you can go to plan B and special summon Dreaming Nemleria to banish your opponent's cards and add banished cards back to your deck or use Necroface to add all cards back to your deck. This deck is also useful because of Dimension Shifter this card can ruin a lot of decks including meta decks that's if you pull it.

 

For the extra deck, you really only need to use Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max and Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe. You can fill the rest of the extra deck with random junk if you want to save money.

(Disclaimer: This deck requires you to play fast. For convenience, change "Card Position" to "Auto" and "Activation Order Settings" to "Off" before the match to save lots of time without doing any major manual labor.)

Greetings! Are you looking for a way to kill your opponent slow and steady? Well, you come into right place.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Fill your side and clear it with "Thunder Crash" while dealing some damage. Then, place Pendulum Monsters on Pendulum Zones.

2) Pendulum Summon Flamvell/Spirit + Clear + Clear + Magicat + Vacuumen. "Vacuumen" has to be in Attack Position, rest can be in any position. Then, equip "Deep-Seated" on Vacuumen and use Vacuumen to send Deep-Seated to GY and deal some damage. However, Deep-Seated will be returned to top of your deck, which can be considered as a loop.

3) Synchro Summon Paladin by using 5 monsters as materials. When you do that, 2 x Clear will draw 2 cards in total and Magicat is going to ask if you want to return a spell from your GY on top of your deck, akin to Deep-Seated. You can activate Magicat or not, up to you.

4) Return all materials used for Paladin to the field with "De-Synchro". Don't forget to place Vacuumen in Attack Position like before. Since you have drawn Deep-Seated, you can use Vacuumen again. Thank goodness Vacuumen's ability isn't hard-once per turn.

5) Repeat step #3 for another time. There, you have to activate "Magicat" and place "De-Synchro" on top of your deck like "Deep-Seated". So, it's for certain you will draw De-Synchro + Deep-Seated every single time.

6) Repeat what was explained in #4 + #5 until the opponent is dead. This will take a long while and I hope you can make it on time. However, chances are highly likely your opponent quits even before all of that.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_description:
"I'm here to see M.F. Purrely." 

"M.F. Purrely?"

A basic pure Purrely deck (post Jan. 2024 list update) that relies heavily on your knowing more on how to play Pokémon TCG than you do Yu-Gi-Oh. The archetype, for those unfamiliar, consists of Level 1 Fairy Monsters with Rank 2 and 7 Xyz Monsters with effects that rely on attaching materials to help grow and develop with their user. Most Purrely decks require a large portion of the deck to be dedicated to its cards, but some other archetypes (i.e., Ghostrick and Spright) can utilize Purrely cards. This, however, is a specifically Purrely-focused deck. 

The Basic Strategy (Look at my funny cat cards) 

Your two biggest main deck cards are the Level 1 Fairies, Purrely and Purrelyly, also known as the Purly Brothe rs: 

Their main goal is to get its Rank 7 Xyz Boss Monster, Expurrely Noir, the most Towers of any Towers that has ever Tower-ed. With Expurrely Noir (1100 Atk, 2800 Def), you have immunity to your opponent's activated effects when you have five or more materials, the ability to spin your opponents monsters at the cost of two materials (which is a Quick Effect with a Level 1 Purrely monster attached as a material). Often, Purrelyly will be your start, as it comes with the most benefits despite having both of its effects be once-per-turn. Purrelyly can search for any non-Quick Play Purrely Cards, and 9 times out of 10 you will end up searching either for My Friend Purrely or Stray Purrely Street. Even though you will use one of these monsters to bring out Expurrely Noir, you will have several ways to bring out other Purrely monsters, since Purrely's effect allows you to excavate the top cards of your deck to add one Purrely Spell/Trap card. 

Another cornerstone piece of the Purrely engine are the Quick-Play Purrely Memories, each of them having the optional effect to special summon a Purrely from your deck monster at the cost of discarding one card. There are four memories with unique main effects as well as an effect when attached to a Purrely Xyz Monster: 

  • Purrely Happy Memory prevents a card from being destroyed by card effect the first time it is until the end phase after its activation. When attached to a Purrely Xyz Monster, it can allow them to attack +1 Monsters on the field per memory attached (Meaning you can make up to 4 attacks against Monsters with one Purrely Xyz). 
  • Purrely Delicious Memory prevents a card from being destroyed by battle until the end phase after its activation. When attached to a Purrely Xyz Monster, it will allow that monster to gain 300+ attack and defense points per card attached as a material, including itself. An Expurrely Noir with 5 materials will gain 1500 attack and defense if it has Delicious Memory as a material, giving it a defense of 4300. This card is limited in TCG format, so sadly your dream of 900+ attack/defense per material remains as only a dream. 
  • Purrely Pretty Memory gives both you and your opponent 1000 LP. However, if this card is attached to a Purrely Xyz, they get the ability to send one card you control to the GY to target one card your opponent controls and attach as material. This is once per turn but does stack with the materials attached to it meaning you can attach up to three cards per turn if you have all three Pretty Memories attached. 
  • Purrely Sleepy Memory makes it so that the first time you would take LP damage after this card was activated turn to 0. When attached to a Purrely Xyz Monster, it gains the effect of allowing you to draw one card on your opponent stand-by phase. Much like Pretty Memory, this effect stacks with the number of memories attached. As of January 2024, this card is semi-limited. 

My Friend Purrely, which will be abbreviated as M.F. Purrely for short, helps get you either Purrely Sleepy Memory or Purrely Delicious Memory. By paying the low, low cost of 500 LP, you can search 3 Purrely cards and add one at random. You will want to aim for either of these two Quick-Play spells (If you activate M.F. Purrely with neither in hand, search for two Sleepy Memories and a Delicious Memory). In addition, another card you want to coincide with M.F. Purrely is Stray Purrely Street, which has three main effects; Attaching a Memory Quick-Play Spell from Deck/GY, preventing Purrely monsters from being targeted by opponent card effects the turn they are summoned, and to create insurance when a Purrely Xyz Monster is removed from field by an opponent's card (This includes destruction by battle or effect, tribute, banish, or bounce/spin). M.F. Purrely also has an insurance policy when it is on the field and your Purrely Xyz is removed from the field. Both work in tandem and will not miss timing, since they are an "if" effect: 

  • Stray Purrely Street (CL1): Special Summons a Purrely monster from Deck or GY. 
  • M.F. Purrely (CL2): Add up to three (3) Purrely Quick-Play Spells with different names from your GY to hand. 

To reach your end goal of that sweet, sweet Towers, Expurrely Noir requires any Rank 2 Monster with 5+ Materials attached to it. This works with any Rank 2, but Purrely Xyz Monsters will give you the easiest time, since you can stack memories/materials on them like pancakes. Each has an effect that allows you to attach a Memory as a material when it activates up to three times per turn, then activate a unique effect upon attaching as a material (NOTE: This is a when effect, cards like Ash Blossom can cause a mistime). The Rank 2 Purrely monsters all require two Level 2 monsters as materials but can be "cheated" out with the effects of the Purly Brothe rs. Each of the Purrely monsters will special summon a Rank 2 Purrely Xyz Monster using a Memory Quick-Play Spell mentioned by that respected monster, with each Purly Broth er having its own way of summoning. Purrely requires you to reveal a memory in hand after activation (Soft once-per-turn), while Purrelyly requires you to target a memory in the GY (Hard once-per-turn). Your Rank 2 Purrely Xyz Monsters corresponds to a respected memory and include: 

  • Epurrely Happiness (Happy Memory) (2000 Atk, 100 Def), which can bounce a Spell/Trap on the field when a memory is attached. If it attacks, it can add a Purrely card from deck to hand and, if it has Purrely Happy Memory, you can halve the attack of a monster on the field. 
  • Epurrely Beauty (Pretty Memory) (1600 Atk, 1100 Def), which can change the position of a monster on the field when a memory is attached. It can negate the effects of a monster on the field. This effect is nice, but it becomes a Quick Effect with Purrely Pretty Memory attached as a material. 
  • Epurrely Plump (Delicious Memory) (200 Atk, 2100 Def), which can banish a monster from the field when a memory is attached. In addition, you can attach up to two Spells/Traps in either GY as materials once per turn, with this being a Quick Effect when Purrely Delicious Memory attached as a material. 
  • Epurrely Noir (Sleepy Memory) (1000 Atk, 2000 Def), which can set a Purrely Trap on the field when a memory is attached. Also, you can bounce a card back to hand at the cost of discarding a card, with the amount of bounces being boosted to two if Purrely Sleepy Memory is attached as a material. 

Since each Rank 2 will already have two materials, getting another three materials is easy with the number of Memories that fill up your deck. Summoning more Purrely monsters as well as using the effects of M.F. Purrely and Stray Purrely Street can help fill up your Purrely with loving care quickly if you know what you are doing. However, the two best routes (With an alternate third one for a possible OTK) for getting Expurrely Noir out are as follows. 

1. Epurrely Noir (The "I Draw 4 On Stand-by Phase" Approach) 

The easiest way, and most beneficial way, that you can get to Expurrely Noir, resulting in your Purrelyeap!? trap (which will target and rank up/down your Purrely Xyz Monster) to bring out Expurrely Noir on your opponent's Standby Phase. For this, you need a few things: 

  • Purrely/Purrelyly on the field. 
  • My Friend Purrely, searching to add Sleepy Memory. 
  • Stray Purrely Street, to ensure you can get 4 materials on your Xyz before the next Standby Phase 
  • One (or more) additional memories to use Epurrely Noir and set one Purrelyeap!?. Bonus if you add Purrely Sharely!? to your decklist, which will target a Rank 2 Purrely Xyz you control and Special Summon a Purrely monster before ranking it into Rank 2 Purrely Xyz and attaching a material from deck based on the materials attached to your targeted monster. 
  1. Bring out Purrelyly or Purrely (Preferably Special Summon Purrelyly, especially if you have Stray Purrely Street on the field, otherwise Normal Summon Purrely), add either your Field Spell (if not already on the field) or M.F. Purrely. Use this to get the correct memory, or an additional Sleepy/Other memory, preferably Pretty or Delicious. The best way to get more memories, if you have already used the effect of M.F. Purrely, is to special summon more Purrelys, which can excavate to add those memories to hand. 
  2. Special Summon Epurrely Noir. 
  3. Attach as many materials to Epurrely Noir as you can, but you will want to aim to set one Purrelyeap!? with its effect and, if you have it in your deck, Purrely Sharely!?. At the bare minimum, you will want Epurrely Noir with four materials before your turn actually ends. 
  4. If you have enough, or cannot do any more than four memories, end your turn. If you have five materials, go into Expurrely Noir. During End Phase, Stray Purrely Street can be used to target your Purrely Xyz Monster to attach either: 
    1. Purrely Sleepy Memory #2, if not attached already. 
    2. Purrely Delicious Memory, to bulk up your E(x)purrely Noir 
    3. Purrely Pretty Memory, if you have both, as well as Sharely!? set. 
  5. On your opponent's Standby Phase, use the effect of Sleepy attached to your Xyz. If you have both Sleepy Memories, draw one in one chain. However, if you want Expurrely Noir, on the second draw, activate Sleepy Memory as CL1, then Purrelyeap!? as CL2 (If you have Sharely!? set, activate it as CL3 to bring out Purrelyly and instantly rank up into Epurrely Beauty with Pretty Memory). After doing so, you can activate Expurrely Noir's effects with both Sleepy Memories to draw twice again (Now you see why Purrely Sleepy Memory is semi-limited). 

The big downside to this approach is that Expurrely Noir will be returned to the deck at the end of the turn after it was summoned with Purrelyeap!?. This card is very risky if you cannot find a way to beat down your opponent or get another Expurrely Noir on the field, which is why it is highly recommended to get AA-ZEUS in your Extra Deck, as Expurrely Noir can just rank up into AA-ZEUS with a lot of materials attached. 

2. Epurrely Plump (The Instant Expurrely Towers Approach) 

  • Epurrely Plump is harder to get out, as Delicious Memory is limited in the TCG format (OCG gets lucky, it's only semi-limited there). You will want to aim to get Plump out, since Plump will eat any Spell/Trap in your GY alongside any Memories attached as a material. For this you will want: 
  • Purrely/Purrelyly on the field. 
  • My Friend Purrely, searching to add Delicious Memory or other memories. 
  • Up to two Spell/Traps in either GY. 
  1. Bring out Purrelyly or Purrely (Preferably Special Summon Purrelyly, especially if you have Stray Purrely Street on the field, otherwise Normal Summon Purrely), add either your Field Spell (if not already on the field) or M.F. Purrely. Use this to get the correct memory, or another memory if you have Delicious already in hand, preferably Pretty or Sleepy. 
  2. Special Summon Epurrely Plump. 
  3. If you have not done so already, use your memories to bring out more Purrely monsters and pitch some spells/traps that you might not use. If Plump is on the field. In addition, if you have two Spells/Traps in your GY, you can attach them as material with Plump's Quick Effect. 
  4. If all has succeeded, your Plump should be stuffed with materials, meaning you can go straight into Expurrely Noir. You do not need to end here, since I would highly recommend getting yourself a second dog, Epurrely Beauty. 

The more materials you can get on Plump, the better. Expurrely Noir, alongside being a tower, can spin a card to the bottom of the deck, which is heavily useful when it still has 5+ Materials. 

3. Epurrely Happiness Beatdown (AKA: The Alternate Win-Con) 

Epurrely Happiness' effects are very much grounds of "Purrely Beatdown" if you're going second. When taking Purrely to tournaments, there have been cases which this proved to be viable (One of my favorite moments was when my Expurrely got tributed for Kurikara only to be beaten down moments later). This set up is the easiest, but hardest to rely on: 

  • Purrely/Purrelyly 
  • Purrely Happy Memory and Purrely Delicious Memory (You can add Delicious with Epurrely Happiness' effect, but you need its effect to prevent a monster your opponent controls from being destroyed by battle) 
  • If you have neither, you will need M.F. Purrely and (possibly) Stray Purrely Street. 
  1. Bring out Purrelyly or Purrely (Preferably Special Summon Purrelyly, especially if you have Stray Purrely Street on the field, otherwise Normal Summon Purrely). If you do not have Happy Memory already, you will need to get one as soon as possible alongside Delicious Memory. 
  2. If you have everything set, bring out Epurrely Happiness. If you have it in hand already, use Purrely Delicious Memory to both attach on Epurrely Happiness as a material and choose the weakest attack position monster on your opponent's side of the field to be immune from destruction by battle. 
  3. If Epurrely Happiness can beat down a monster, do so. Its effect will allow you to not only half the attack of an opposing monster but also add a Purrely card from deck. For this, add another Happy Memory. Epurrely Happiness, with three Purrely Happy Memories, can attack up to four times on a single monster, halving its attack on each strike.  

Often times, you won't even need to go into Expurrely Noir, as you will most likely bring the LP of your opponent down to zero at this moment, depending on how strong you get Epurrely Happiness to be. However, in the event that your opponent is hanging on by a thread, you can go into Expurrely Noir immediately after you enter Main Phase 2. If you understood that Epurrely Happiness can add any card, you can also add an additional essential card for Purrely, such as Stray Purrely Street so that Expurrely Noir can get another material on End Phase. 

Additional Cards (More toys for your kitties to play with) 

  • When considering how Purrely spams several Level 1 monsters frequently, Sylvan Princessprite is a Rank 1 that can be easily brought out with Purrely. If you spam memories to bring out Purrelys to excavate, you can go into Sylvan and use its effect to excavate the top card of your deck if it is a Spell or Trap Card. You will rarely whiff on this if your deck primarily focuses on Spell cards. Lyrilusc - Assembled Nightingale also serves as an alternative Rank 1 approach, which can be used to attack directly and go into AA-ZEUS, which can be useful against King Calamity-locking decks like Centurion. 
  • Two Link Monsters that work well with the Level 1-centric Purrely deck are Relinquished Anima and Linkurboh. Anima is a going second tool for players who forget about column plays. Since Purrely spams Level 1 monsters frequently, you often end up with 2-3 Purrely monsters on the board. Since Anima requires a Level 1 monster, you can easily put this in a Link zone conveniently adjacent to a monster your opponent controls and relies on. This pairs well if you have a Purrely Xyz that has Pretty Memory, as you can send one (either the newly attached Monster or Anima) to get rid of another monster your opponent controls. Linkuriboh is not necessary for this deck but has its uses when you feel like your end board needs the effect to set a monster's attack to 0. 
  • Sky Striker Ace - Azalea and Protector of the Agents - Moon are there to prevent flood gates, with PotA - Moon useful for floodgates like Skill Drain or the (now limited) Gozen/TCBOO/Rivalry (As a Light-Fairy Link, you can use its effect to tribute itself to the GY for cost and destroy one other card your opponent controls. Azalea is quite easy to summon, since Purrely is an archetype of both Light and Dark main deck monsters you can easily summon. 
  • There are several opportunities in this deck to use your Rank 1 and 2 Xyz Monsters, and even your Rank 7 Towers, to go into Downerd Magician and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS. It is not always important to do so, but it's a bargaining chip you can use so that your opponent has a target to go after instead of Expurrely Noir. 
  • Droll and Lock Bird can be really useful as a Level 1 monster. Oh, it's also a hand trap, I guess. If you somehow need to rank up into a monster that needs a Level 1, Droll and Lock Bird can be summoned. If you really want to, you can prevent your opponent from adding cards to the deck after they add something. Run some Droll and Lock Birds in the main deck to help with having some Level 1/Hand Trap consistencies. 
  • Time Thief Hack is an odd choice, but it is a useful replacement for Purrely Delicious Memory #2 and #3. It is not necessary to run, but it has its uses: Being able to allow your Xyz Monsters to both gain 300+ Attack/Defense per material and, if holding a material that was from the opponent's deck, attack directly. 
  • Purrely works well with some floodgates, including Grave of the Super Ancient Organism and Rivalry of Warlords. Summon Limit has its periodic uses on Game 2/3 when going first, especially after you have set up your necessary board, but be sure you are careful when using this card. You can unintentionally mess your work up when Summon Limit prevents you from going into Expurrely Noir. Of course, you can get rid of it with Pretty Memory.

This is obviously not the ideal Purrely deck, but it has seen a lot of results in the past against other decks. I have had a lot of fun finding ways to modify and craft this deck. This is based on other Purrely decks I have seen being used on both YGOPro as well as some other decks I have faced. Other cards you can consider for side deck include Nibiru the Primal Being/Kaiju (Gameciel or others) or Herald of the Abyss. Some other (sometimes pricier) options include I:P Masquerena with S:P Little Knight, Triple Tactics Thrust, and Super Starslayer TY-PHON.

deck_excerpt: Evol Nemleria  / 2nd Castle Town CS Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (OCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: @nikorinch

Tournament: 2nd Castle Town CS – January 14th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Introduction

As a Nephthys fan, I've been pretty disappointed with how the deck performs nowadays in comparison to other Ritual decks. Sure, Conductor of Nephthys is an insanely powerful retrain that the deck so desperately needed to extend its combos, but it wasn't enough. Enter Libromancers!

 

To summarize both archetypes, the Nephthys cards revolve around summoning the Ritual spellcasters, and then using them to go into the other Nepthys cards. They accomplish this with the powerful Conductor of Nephthys, who essentially brings out two other bodies onto the field for free. Their Ritual Spell, Rebirth of Nephthys, can also non-target pop a card under certain conditions, which is very useful. I recommend playing the solo gate to see them in action.

 

Libromancers are focused on generating lots of card advantage and Ritual summoning multiple times in a single turn, while also being fairly straightforward to pilot, as most of their cards loop into each other. All they need to get going is a non-Ritual Libromancer (preferably Libromancer Fire or Libromancer Geek Boy) and any other Ritual monster in your hand, including a Nephthys.

 

As a disclaimer, this deck will mainly be carried by the Libromancer cards, simply because they are far more powerful and consistent than Nephthys (Konami please print more support for my girls). However, the Nephthys cards will provide some much-appreciated extra support. For example, Pre-Preparation of Rites gets you both Rebirth of Nephthys and Devotee of Nephthys. If you have any non-Ritual Libromancers in your hand, you can get the Libromancer line started from there. Overall, the deck is pretty simple to use, with a lot of room to extend further.

 

Some combos and tips

  1. Libromancer line (Libromancer Fire and any Ritual): Libromancer Fire reveals a Ritual monster and summon, effect to search Libromancer Geek Boy, Geek boy eff to summon and search Libromancer Origin Story, Origin Story eff search Libromancer First Appearance, First Appearance adds a Libromancer Ritual monster, and finally Ritual summon.

  2. Nephthys line (Rebirth of Nephthys + Conductor of Nephthys): Rebirth of Nephthys to summon Conductor of Nephthys (if you use Devotee of Nephthys or Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys as tribute, you can pop a card for free as well), Conductor eff to summon second Devotee from deck, Devotee eff to summon Disciple of Nephthys, Disciple to pop and search another Conductor. Link off into the Link-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver (preferably leave Conductor on the field) to search a level 8 and recycle Rebirth. NOTE: If you have any non-Ritual Libromancers in your hand, make sure to play those while you have still have Rituals in your hand.

  3. Going first example: Continuing from the Nephthys line above, revive Devotee by destroying whatever Nephthys card you added from the Link-2, use both to go into Gigantic Spright, Gigantic eff to summon Diviner of the Herald, Diviner send Herald of the Arc Light to the GY to add another Ritual card. You should have Gigantic Spright, Diviner, and Conductor on the field now, in addition to any Libromancers if you had any (like Libromancer Doombroker with Libromancer Intervention set). Link off Diviner and Gigantic for Spright Elf, Elf eff to revive Disciple, link off Disciple and Conductor for I:P Masquerena. Now you can summon Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax on your opponent’s turn.

  4. Going second: Standard Libromancer Fireburst OTK line (see combo #1). You can clear pieces of the opponent’s board before attacking, with cards like Libromancer Origin Story, Rebirth of Nephthys, or Dyna Mondo. Another good OTK option is Borrelsword Dragon.

  5. Diviner of the Herald: This is the deck’s main Normal Summon. Use her effect to dump Herald of Arc Light (or Elder Entity N'tss if you’re going second and already have a Ritual in hand). She will then be level 6, which is perfect for Ritual summoning or using her with Libromancer Fire to go into Baronne de Fleur .

  6. Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys: This is the level 8 Ritual Nephthys monster. You mainly use it as fodder for Rebirth of Nephthys or a search target for the Link-2 Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver. Rarely do you actually summon it, but if you do, it has a pretty great non-target destruction effect and comes back every turn if it’s destroyed!

 

Tech Options

  1. Libromancer Magigirl and Libromancer Mystigirl: The idea with Magigirl is that you use her effect to Ritual summon Mystigirl on your opponent’s turn for a monster negate. She’s fine, but is outclassed by Dyna Mondo. Mystigirl might be worth playing though.

  2. Libromancer Firestarter and Libromancer Bonded: These two cards are mostly irrelevant, but both are Pre-Prep targets if you want more search power.

  3. Nephthys, the Sacred Flame: This is the almighty Nephthys boss monster, a Link-3 that basically requires 3 Ritual monsters to be any good and is essentially a more expensive Avramax. It’s not really worth the effort to bring out, but it is hilarious in low power events where Avramax is banned, such as the Ritual Festival, since it has the potential to be a 4800 attack pseudo-Towers.

  4. Fire Kings: Not really a tech option, but should be noted anyway. The only Fire King monster currently in Master Duel that really matters is Fire King High Avatar Garunix because he is searchable off of the Link-2 Nephthys. The rest of the Fire Kings are not as useful because the Nephthys spellcasters are Wind and not Fire, so there isn’t too much other overlap.

  5. Secret Village of the Spellcasters: The Nephthys girls are all spellcasters, which means you can use Secret Village to lock your opponent out of spells. However, even the strongest Nephthys girl (Conductor) has only 2000 attack, which means she can easily be destroyed by battle. Luckily, both Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax and Nephthys, the Sacred Flame (the aforementioned Link-3) provide battle protection.

  6. Imperial Iron Wall: Since this deck relies on the GY often, we don’t want our cards to get banished, so this is an excellent floodgate to play. We don’t really use any banish effects ourselves either, so it doesn’t hinder us at all. Not really necessary to play, but nice to have in the current meta.

 

Closing Thoughts

I hope you enjoy playing this deck! There are way more combos and techs you could do than the ones I've listed here since there are no summoning restrictions on any of the cards, so play around and have fun!
Drawwww

deck_excerpt: Masquerade Tax Block ft. Number C6 + Chain Energy + Toll
deck_description:
Hello there! It seems your opponent is trying to evade paying taxes. Let's remind them of their duties with Masquerade, shall we? Jokes aside, this deck is similar to another block deck I made with Kashtira Shangri-Ira but instead of zone block, your opponent can't pay LP to "draw the out".

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant at least one flower to opposing side with "Black Garden" but it's alright if you grow more.

2) XYZ Summon Number 60 by using 2 x Cthugua as materials. Then, pass Number 60 to opposing side by replacing a flower with "Mystic Box".

3) Synchro Summon Stardust by using Librarian + Tuner as materials. Then, activate "Theater of the Branded" and Fusion Summon Masquerade by using Aluber + Soulkius in-hand as materials.

4) Activate Soulkius in GY to Special Summon it to your field. Next, XYZ Summon Number 6 by using Soulkius + Stardust as materials. Then, overlay into Number C6 with Barian's Force.

5) Equip Number 60 with Number C6. Then, activate Number C6 to set your opponent's LP to 100.

6) First, activate "Toll". Next, "Chain Energy". Then, set "Mask of Restrict" and end your turn. Finally, activate "Mask of Restrict" during your opponent's Draw Phase. Therefore, your opponent is completely locked down...

  • Mask of Restrict: Denies tributing for either sides, which blocks Kaiju-related cards. So, your opponent can't get rid of Masquerade and draw the out.
  • Masquerade: Requires 600 LP to pay and activate cards/effects from anywhere. Only applies to your opponent.
  • Toll: Requires 500 LP to pay and attack, which applies to either players.
  • Chain Energy: Requires 500 LP to pay and do these from hand, which applies to both sides...
    • Normal Summon
    • Special Summon
    • Set
    • Activate cards

7) Since your opponent can't do anything but pass the turn to you, you can attack and close the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" + "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Number 6: Chronomaly Atlandis" + "Number C6: Chronomaly Chaos Atlandis" can be found within "Timeworn Legacies" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR!

- "Masquerade the Blazing Dragon" can be found within "The Opening Act of an Apocalypse" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Fabled Soulkius" can be found within "Fabled Gods" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Rank-Up-Magic Barian's Force" can be found within "Sword of the Seventh One" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- As of this writing, you can find these cards below from Timed Packs to save SR materials:

  • Mannadium Trisukta >>> Indomitable Pride >>> 30 SR
  • Sacred Sword of Seven Stars >>> Mighty Contenders >>> 30 SR (Can be also found in "Celestial Dragon and Bear" Secret Pack)
  • Aluber the Jester of Despia >>> Beginning of the Next Journey >>> 30 SR (Can be also found in "The Opening Act of an Apocalypse" Secret Pack)

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Smash the board with the Ancient Spirits!
deck_description:
Playing with this deck is pretty straightforward. Just Bring about the strong Ancient Gear fusion monsters ASAP on the field. For this, there included a bunch of fusion cards which have been added in this deck.

In case of opponents which bring the monster which can eliminate your monsters with monster effects. First try to bring the Ancient Gear Megagolem in the field which can ensure several other substitutes in case it gets in the GY from monster effects.

And lastly, fusion Summon Chaos Gear Giant to bring about absolute destruction.

deck_excerpt: Trickstar Lycoris FTK ft. Light Stage + Dark Room + Exchange
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, you will have fun while giving your opponent nightmares. Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, play "Chain Summoning" to gain two more Normal Summons. Fortunately, you can decide how to do...

  • Librarian / Panda / Ravenous / Ancient / Mist / Shamisen / BLS / Saryuja / Any Spell >>> Reload/Acquisitiveness >>> CS
  • Any Spell >>> Ravenous >>> CS
  • Integrator >>> Trisukta >>> CS
  • Librarian >>> Formula/Martial/Integrator/Trisukta/Ravenous/Mist >>> CS

2) If your opponent doesn't have any cards in their hands, which is possible if you go second, Synchro Summon Mist by using Ancient + Non-Tuner + Tuner as materials. Then, return at least one Main Deck Monster or Spell/Trap to their hand and unlock "Exchange" loop, of which I'm going to explain later. Otherwise, Synchro Summon Ravenous with either same materials like before or Ancient + Formula.

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Black Luster Soldier (BLS) with his ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Meanwhile, send one copy of "Primal Seed" to Banish Zone (BZ).

4) With Saryuja + Chain Summoning, bring forth 3 x Lycoris. If you must, spare one Main Monster Zone (MMZ) for 3rd Lycoris by banishing a monster you have in MMZ with BLS.

5) While holding 1 x Primal Seed + 2 x Exchange, and perhaps not holding any Quick-Play spells for safety, activate Light Stage + 3 x Dark Room. Then, play Exchange...

  • If your opponent is actually smart, they might try stealing either "Primal Seed" or "Exchange" to stop the combo. As if it will happen...
    • If they take "Primal Seed", you can take "Primal Seed" back with 2nd copy of "Exchange" you have. Then, you can fetch both Exchange cards in BZ with "Primal Seed" by targeting 1st copy of "Primal Seed" and 1st copy of "Exchange". You have to repeat this step again, which is what I meant with "Exchange" loop.
    • If they take "Exchange", similar to above, you can fetch "Exchange" with "Primal Seed" loop. There, you can take stolen copy of "Exchange" back and even if they steal "Primal Seed", you can take stolen copy of "Primal Seed" back. This is actually same loop like above but with different order of events.

6) With "Exchange" being played, you have given your opponent a card, which triggers Lycoris + Light Stage + Dark Room to deal enormous damage...

  • While 3 x Dark Room cards are resolving, you would actually go up to Chain Link as 18. Once for each from 3 x Lycoris + Three times in total from Light Stage thanks to 3 x Lycoris, that's why. 1 x Dark Room deals damage 6 times, which is Chain Link as 6. Thus, 3 x Dark Room would end up with Chain Link as 18.
  • However, Master Duel has a Chain Link limit. If you try to go beyond Chain Link 16, first 16 of them will happen in one big Chain Link. Then, the rest will go on as new series of Chain Link.

7) Repeat these steps explained in #5 + #6 until your opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning" can be collected by purchasing "Spiral Spear Strike" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Mannadium Trisukta" can be found within "Indomitable Pride" Timed Pack to save 30 SR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

- "Trickstar Lycoris" + "Trickstar Light Stage" can be found within "Essence of Flora and Ocean" Secret Pack to save 90 SR and 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Exchange" + "Mist Wurm" + "Dark Room of Nightmare" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 240 SR and 60 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 870 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!
