deck_excerpt: Drag your opponents down under the waves with this Synchro deck!
deck_description:
Icejade is one of my favorite archetypes ever, and I generally like WATER strategies whenever they're playable. And surprisingly... in Theme Chronicle this is an entirely playable strategy! Not the best thing you could be playing, but one that can grind it out with the best and get you the wins for those sweet, sweet gems.

This decklist is an altered version of one I actually encountered in the event, so I cannot take credit for making this. I will, however, explain the deck to the best of my ability to hopefully make it easier to learn. It's not an especially difficult deck, but information can help you understand how to build your own version and thus be able to improve upon it should you choose to do so.

The deck is comprised of about two engines made up of three archetypes, the Atlantean+Deep Sea providing Synchro plays and material, while the Icejade cards provide further material and a control tool in Icejade Erosion. It's relatively consistent to get into something across the deck, as both engines net you at least one disruption if you don't get interrupted and decent follow-up for next turn.

Icejade

  • 2x Icejade Aegirine searches any Icejade Spell/Trap on summon, and then revives a WATER if your opponent targets her in any way. The exact target for her search depends on the game state, though I usually favor Erosion if I opened Aegirine with no other relevant cards in hand.
  • 2x Icejade Tremora allows us effectively free Special Summons of WATER monsters from our hand, just generically useful. If an Icejade is destroyed (including by your own cards) while Tremora's in the GY, she can also banish herself to summon an Icejade from hand or GY.
  • 2x Icejade Ran Aegirine is an excellent last support card for Icejade, as is still extremely good here. Discarding a WATER (which triggers the Atlanteans, more on that later) allows you to summon her plus an Icejade token. This token locks you into WATER while its on the field, but the material allows you to make a WATER Level 10 Synchro (though they're banned in this event, so no Aegirine Gymir or Chengying for us here) or a WATER Link-2 (Abyssalacia or Coral Anemone, probably). 
  • 1x Icejade Creation Kingfisher is a method of removal and a bit of extra extension if we need it. Entirely removable if you so desire, but being able to bounce an opponent's card back to hand is useful enough that I keep it around.
  • 2x Icejade Cradle searches any Icejade monster. Not a once per turn, either.
  • 1x Icejade Manifestation allows you either Foolish Burial or Emergency Teleport an Icejade if you control a WATER and your opponent has a monster on field or in grave.
  • 1x Icejade Erosion is a once per turn repeatable negate of any card on the field for the cost of destroying an Icejade monster you control. And if your opponent gets clever and tries to banish your WATER monsters from field (or shuffles them into hand/deck), Erosion lets you summon an Icejade straight from your deck.

Atlantean+Deep Sea

  • 2x Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince is a potent card, though not quite a one card starter. He can send an Atlantean from deck to grave as cost (which triggers the effects of Infantry and Dragoon) to search an Atlantean of choice. Usually you send Dragoons to search Heavy Infantry, but occasionally sending Infantry to destroy something can be useful depending on board state. 
  • 1x Atlantean Heavy Infantry grants you a second normal summon for Sea Serpent monsters, and if sent to the GY to activate a WATER monster effect (IE, sent as cost) it destroys a face-up card your opponent controls.
  • 3x Deep Sea Diva is a classic Tuner, and still a potent one. By Normal Summoning her (not Special Summon), you can summon any level 3 or lower Sea Serpent straight from your deck. 
  • 2x Deep Sea Minstrel is one of our targets for Diva, and more importantly a tool to get rid of handtraps so you can play uncontested. You can discard Minstrel and another WATER (as cost, so Atlanteans are triggered by this, so Dragoons+Minstrel is a very fun opening hand) to look at your opponent's hand and banish one card from it until the end phase.
  • 1x Guitar Gurnards Duonigis is the other target for Diva. It can double the level of one Level 4 or lower WATER for the turn, allowing access higher level Synchros off just Diva. It also banishes cards from your opponent's deck equal to the number of WATER monsters you control when it was Special Summoned, which is important for Deep Sea Repiteur since it needs your opponent to have banished cards.
  • 3x Atlantean Dragoons. Send this as cost (for another monster) to search a Sea Serpent, and that's basically it. The on-field effect is not relevant ever, since the Sea Serpents we run have very low attack in the first place.
  • 2x Deep Sea Aria to search Diva (or another Sea Serpent, but usually Diva), if you can get another WATER into the grave (which is not especially difficult).

Non-Engine

  • 3x Ash Blossom, 3x Maxx 'C', 2x Called By the Grave, 1x Crossout Designator, 2x Infinite Impermanence. Handtraps and anti-handtraps, these are generically useful and all legal in this event. I'd be running these in any deck I'd run for this deck.
  • 1x One for One to summon Neptabyss for the cost of a discard. Note that it cannot activate the effects of the Atlanteans, since One for One is not a WATER monster.
  • 3x Synchro Overtake. By revealing Deep Sea Repiteur, you can either add Diva to your hand or Special Summon her. Diva's effect only activates when she is Normal Summoned, so you may just want to add her to your hand and normal her.
  • 1x Moulinglacia the Elemental Lord. If you have exactly 5 WATER monsters in your grave, you can SS it from your hand, and then forcibly discard two random cards from your opponent's hand. The only weakness is that if it is removed from the field, you skip the Battle Phase of your next turn. This can be prove annoying, but the card itself is potent enough to be worth the downside.

Extra Deck (only one copy of each card, I generally haven't found too much need for extra copies of anything)

  • Tatsunoko allows one to Synchro Summon using cards in your hand as material, allowing you to turn an otherwise off-line Icejade Tremora into a Level 8 Synchro (or any other combination to make a Synchro with a Level 3 Tuner, use your imagination). You can make this with Deep Sea Diva+Neptabyss.
  • Herald of the Arc Light is an omni-negate+minor floodgate, made using Diva+Infantry if you so desire. The GY effect does not have any use in this deck, as we don't play any Rituals.
  • Deep Sea Repiteur is required for Synchro Overtake to function, and is fairly functional regardless. While her on-field effect is mostly irrelevant even in this lower powered format, her effect when sent to the GY is just a straight Monster Reborn for Level 5+ WATER monsters, though you're locked into WATER for the rest of the turn afterward.
  • Coral Dragon, a classic bit of removal for Synchro decks and one easily made with Diva+Dragoons. Discard (which does count for the Atlantean cards' effect when discarded) to destroy a card on field. And if it gets sent to the GY, you even get a draw.
  • Deep Sea Prima Donna is a surprisingly strong card, one that is basically limited by the rest of WATER decks not being strong enough to really leverage its power. Put a banished card back into your opponent's hand to summon any Level 4 or below WATER monster from your deck (or add it your hand). Make this using Diva+Guitar (by using Guitar's effect on Diva). When she's sent to the GY, she'll even shuffle any banished card back to the deck (including whatever you banished with Minstrel's effect, if you so desire). 
  • White Aura Whale is one of our two main bosses (at least, ones you'll realistically summon), and is our offensive tool for getting inton a game winning state. On summon it's basically Lightning Storm's anti-monster effect, and it can attack twice on monsters while inflicting piercing battle damage. If it ends up destroyed, you can banish another WATER from your GY to revive it as a Tuner, which is not a once per turn.
  • Adamanicpator Risen - Dragite is our other boss monster, and our defensive tool going first. If you have a WATER in grave, you can negate a Spell/Trap every turn. The other effect is useless in this deck, since we run no other Rocks. Both this card and White Aura Whale can be made by Diva+Guitar (using Guitar effect on itself to make it a 6), or with Prima Donna+Neptabyss.
  • I:P Masquerena is a generic Link-2 you can go into if you have to for whatever reason. I haven't had it as part of an end-board yet, nor do I find opportunities where I wouldn't rather make something else, but it works and we do not have a lot of good alternatives.
  • Mistar Boy is just WATER support to help boost our damage. It's generally a struggle to OTK, so we'll take as much help as we can get. Also grabs a WATER and adds to hand when destroyed by your opponent, which is helpful.
  • Mermail Abysslacia is a back-up plan, and a generically solid Link-2 for the deck. Her effect to search a Mermail is not applicable to this deck, as we do not have main-deck Mermails (none fit especially well, though Abyssdine, Abyssteua, and/or Abysspike might be generically good enough to consider), but her effect when the opponent destroys her is a solid advantage generator by allowing you to both Foolish Burial a WATER (for cost) then revive a WATER of your choice. Since you rarely get OTK'd in this format (in my experience), you can use this to sit on if you can get two monsters onto the field (that are Fish/Sea Serpent/Aqua) and maybe be able to follow up next turn.
  • Knightmare Phoenix is generic Spell/Trap removal that's easily made.
  • Marincess Coral Anemone revives a WATER that's below 1500 ATK. Easy to make, and helps push damage in general.
  • Knightmare Unicorn is easily made removal for anything that has an effect when destroyed (or can't be destroyed), since it shuffles the target back into deck.
  • Knightmare Gryphon I have never made and probably won't ever make. It's a lot of investment for a psuedo-Skill Drain, and we're generally better off with other tools most of the time.
  • Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is in a similar boat. I just slotted him in because there's little else to put in. Avramax made with I:P probably isn't outable by most decks, though, so you can definitely get some benefit if you need to.

Try it.

Folks this deck has actually surprised me with how often it's able to win.  I'm sorry for the long text but this is just one combo you can do and the deck has dozens! Let me know if a more in depth guide is wanted, I really think this deck has potential to be a solid option.

There are many lines but your full max power combo is, Ostinato send Sonata and Soprano (even if both Sopranos are in hand Ostinato allows you to use cards from hand), fusion summon Bacha, Effect of Bacha to summon Refrain (zone placement matters in this deck as our link Bloom requires her bottom left and bottom right zones be empty to work so place Bacha and Refrain right underneath the Extra Monster Zones and then other Special Summons away from whatever zones you will use for Bloom, anyway), Effect of Refrain to add Couplet, Effect of Couplet when added to hand to special summon Soprano in the far left or far right zone, Effect of Soprano to add Sonata to hand, Couplet in pendelum zone, Effect of Couplet to add Concerto, special summon Sonata, Link Refrain and Sonata into Bloom (place her where she has 2 available zones to summon to),  Effect of Bloom discarding any card that is not the Concerto we added, special summon Aria and Elegy, Activate Concerto using Bacha Couplet and Bloom as materials to fusion summon Etoile, Chain Link 1 Bacha to special summon Sonata CL2 and CL3 Refrain and Couplet, Effect of Soprano to fusion summon Schuberta, Effect of Concerto to draw a card.

Okay so what do we have? We can not be targeted, can not be destroyed by battle, can not be destroyed by card effects, we can spin 3 cards from either grave as a quick effect, we have spin back up to 4 cards to our opponents hand as a quick effect and we have 5 other cards in our hand.

To a lot of decks, this is a complete blowout as they have no way of clearing our board.  To some other decks, they need to summon Zeus to send our cards to grave which we can spin back their XYZs before they can even do it.  TY-PHON also allows them to remove one card from our field non targetting which we can also just spin back before they can activate the effect.  Dragite can also do it if it reveals a bunch of rocks but yet again we can spin it back before it even activates.  The board is essentially a wall that tells your opponent we are going to turn 3 whether you like it or not (unless they Super Poly which then yikes we got a game on our hands)

Anyway that's it! I hope you enjoyed and try out the deck.  Again let me know if you want more combo lines or just discussions on different match ups or an in depth look at ratios and cards included.  Thanks for checking out my list!

-JinxMyLux

deck_excerpt: Witch Doctor of Sparta FTK ft. One for One + A/D Changer + Wanghu
deck_description:
Hey there! This is a FTK deck of Sparta, where you pull out monsters from your Main Deck to deal damage. Let's see...

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have 2 x Sparta + 1 x Wanghu in-hand, send at least two of them to GY but you can send all as well. You can reserve the remaining to bring forth with Saryuja later on. Here are your means as to how to send them to GY...

  • Ancient >>> If you open up only with Panda, use Sparta/Wanghu + Tuner as materials for Librarian.
  • Dugares/Ravenous >>> Discard one/two of your combo pieces to GY.
  • One for One >>> Similar to Dugares, you can send one of your combo pieces to GY.

2) After you have Link Summoned Saryuja, if possible, Special Summon remaining combo piece with Saryuja. If it's Wanghu, send it to GY with "Self-Mummification".

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, clear all of your Main Monster Zones (MMZ) excluding one where Chaos is with "Self-Mummification".

4) Revive monsters named "Sparta >>> Sparta >>> Wanghu" with "Monster Reborn" in explained order to not destroy anything by accident with Wanghu. Then, send "A/D Changer" to GY...

  • If Changer is in your hand, play "One for One" and send Changer as cost for "One for One".
  • If Changer is in your deck, play "One for One" and target Changer as effect for "One for One". Changer will be destroyed by Wanghu and sent to GY, so it's all good. This also starts triggering 2 x Sparta monsters to deal 2 x 500 = 1000 damage in total.

5) Refill your deck with Level 1 monsters thanks to "Pot of Avarice". However, if you get any in your hand, put them back to deck with "Pot of Generosity".

6) Activate Changer in GY to banish it and change battle position of a monster. Then, fetch Changer to your hand with "Primal Seed".

7) When Changer is in your hand, play "One for One" and target Changer in-hand to bring forth Level 1 dudes from your Main Deck. As mentioned in #4, 2 x Sparta will deal 2 x 500 = 1000 damage in total. Then, Wanghu clears Level 1 dudes, so you can play "One for One" again.

8) Repeat these steps explained in #5 + #6 + #7 until your opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "King Tiger Wanghu" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: probably not the best build, but pretty affordable!
deck_description:
My take on a budget pend pile. The obvious swap-outs are Accesscode Talker for Borrelsword, S:P Little Knight for Spheres, and a psy-frame package (3 of PSY-Framegear Delta plus a copy each of PSY-Framegear Gamma and PSY-Framelord Lambda). If you want to keep it even more budget, swap Ty-Phon for The Zombie Vampire or a generic rank 4 ( Tornado Dragon or Time Thief Redoer are probably best.) Also could swap something out for Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon but that's only if you want an easy-to-make Baronne before you start your Dracoslayer setups.

Maindeck is the Superheavy Package, Dracoslayer core (plus Amorphage stuff for extension and Greed plays going first), and a semi-standard handtrap lineup. Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion is a meta call, as it hits Fire King, Labyrnth, and Mannadium pretty effectively. Could be swapped for maindeck Droll at your preference. Swap-ins include Secret Village of the Spellcasters for a copy of Dinomight since you can consistently access at least 1 field spell with Majesty Pegasus. Kashtira Fenrir is an option, but the maindeck is tight on space as is, and the one extra interruption or slightly quicker Baronne isn't great. And if you can afford it, Sky Iris setups fundamentally change the deck, giving you access to OTK power and better endboard interruptions with Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon. There's also a build that aims to turbo out Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord with Majesty Pegasus to search out Amorphous Persona, but that's a different deck in some ways, and having fewer handtraps is a death sentence in the current format. If you are going for that build then definitely swap Ty-Phon with Zombie Vampire for an easy out to the lock that'll help you make further plays on turn 3. 

The extra is pretty standard, going off of other lists with some meta-dependent choices. The ideal end board is usually 2-3 negate sources, Zealantis or Beyond, and a hand trap or two. Obviously, the Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon version of the deck can do more, don't expect the same power from this build, your board will be more control-oriented.

For the side, Ghost Ogre is mainly there for Fire King (you want to pop Fire King Island after the first activation), so that could be swapped out with Anti-Spell Fragrance depending on the meta. Zombie World (searchable off of Majesty Pegasus)  and Shifter are matchup-dependent but mainly there for the FK matchup and the increase in Tearlaments. Droll and Nibiru are generically good and could be swapped out with a board breaker of your choice ( think Dark Ruler No More or Forbidden Droplet ). Greed helps against certain decks going first, permitted you can fully set up, but isn't great against decks like Fire King and Labyrnth. Scarlight is the best time card for the deck, in my experience. Veiler is a worse Infinite Impermanence, but with the Superheavy engine, it's a bit better to not brick half your hand before you can even play in the event you're going second. Kaiju's are also viable outside of a graveyard-focused Meta. Lava Golem and co. are good in the event Centur-Ion and Purrely pop back up but don't worry too much about them for the current format. Bystials just don't do enough, and your maindeck is already tight, would not recommend. 

If you have any suggestions or input on the build//writing, DM me @SwagCrona on Twitter!

deck_excerpt: Can go turn 1 easily, and often OTK's or locks the field well enough for a win turn 2
deck_description:
Diamond!

Can go turn 1 easily, and often OTK's or locks the field well enough for a win turn 2. Tons of flexibility with the deck, either Iblee locking (won't ever be a permanent lock, but opponents will still spend some resources removing it), or Dogmatika for negates/dumping your Extra Deck to clear their board, Dogmatika Alba for big body on Turn 2, and you can easily enough get 2 Mikanko out Turn 2 or 1 Mikanko with Double Edged Sword to sweep turn 2. Lots of paths toward damage and board clearing.

You want to end your board with Hu-Li with Metalsilver Armor attached. Lots of decks struggle to target only the spell if they're already low on resources. Turn 1 you can bring out Hu-Li and use the trap on turn 2 to attach metalsilver to her as well. Can use Iblee on Turn 1 to set up Dogmatika as well.

deck_excerpt: Last Turn Win ft. Abyss + Wall + Thunder + Broken + Kristya
deck_description:
Greetings! This deck is quite an unorthodox one, as we will try to win with "Last Turn". Before you all say, yes, I know "Last Turn" is banned in MD and so are in TCG/OCG. However, its rulings are really complex and got me intrigued. So, I decided to make it simpler for you and just take the deck as if "Last Turn" wasn't banned, where you could play like usual under MD banlist.

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, play Burning >>> Broken combo. If you play Bamboo Swords in explained order, you can skip your opponent's Main Phase 1. The reason as to why I did is that the opponent's turn can be skipped by jumping right into End Phase, if you activate "Thunder of Ruler" in Standby Phase. You see, by omitting Battle Phase right after Main Phase 1, game automatically jumps into End Phase...

  • If you still don't believe me, you can look at these pages.

2) XYZ Summon "Abyss Dweller" by using 2 x Cthugua as materials. Activate this card when it's your opponent's turn, so that your opponent can't activate anything in GY when "Last Turn" has sent your opponent's belongings to GY.

3) Special Summon Kristya with Saryuja. Then, set all Traps and end your turn. When your opponent's turn begins, do these in order:

  1. Activate Abyss + Wall in Draw Phase. Wall is needed to adjust your LP, so that you can activate "Last Turn", if you set your LP lower than or equal to 1000.
  2. Remember what I told you in #1? You can activate "Thunder of Ruler" in Standby Phase.
  3. When the game has just hit into End Phase, activate "Last Turn" and select Kristya...
    • Everything from both sides except the card you have chosen will be sent to GY, which was covered in #1 in case opponent tries to pull off a dirty trick.
    • Then, your opponent tries to Special Summon a monster from their deck in face-up Attack Position and two monsters are going to clash. Battle damage is disregarded, so neither player is going to be hurt. Whichever stands out at End Phase is going to win, otherwise it will be a draw. However, there is a catch: Your opponent can't Special Summon anything thanks to Kristya, so you actually win this one.

4) Congratulations, you win the duel with "Last Turn"!

 

That's all for this deck. Let me know if you have any suggestions to improve this deck and have fun in Master Duel!

Então, vou escrever em português e você gringo que queira ler isso aqui, use o tradutor kkkkk.

Enfim, essa lista de Solfachord eu fiz muito pensando em como deixá-la o mais competitiva e ao mesmo tempo original o possível, vamos a algumas explicações.

Eu decidi não usar a mecânica de Supreme King (Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm) por um motivo muito simples de: ainda que seja muito boa e te dar um monstro na mesa praticamente de graça e uma pendulum scale mais baixa possível, ela acaba atrapalhando um pouco o plano principal desse deck que é uma mesa que tenha a GranSolfachord Coolia em campo, pois ela depende da pendulum scale ser ímpar e 0 é considerado par, então fica muito meh fazer tudo para deixar o monstro assinatura do deck praticamente inútil.

Outra coisa a se destacar, o Kashtira Riseheart no deck além do Kashtira Fenrir, bem, isso me veio a mente enquanto eu testava algumas ideias no deck e lembrei que a carta da Number 76: Harmonizer Gradielle existe. Pra quem não entendeu vou tentar explicar melhor, é natural que os decks principalmente não meta (e nesse caso necessitado de 2 ou mais cartas para de fato combar) venham com um tijolinho na mão, pois bem, se você fizer a proeza de puxar o Kashtira Fenrir (o que não é tão difícil tendo em vista que além dos 3 Kashtira Fenrir você também vai ter 3 Pot of Prosperity, cada um podendo escavar até 6 cartas, então é bem provável que você consiga) você consegue usar o efeito dele puxando o Kashtira Riseheart, e usando os dois você faz a Number 76: Harmonizer Gradielle que é uma literal tower contra decks de fogo (cof cof meta de Fire King), e óbvio que como todo plano esse também é suscetível a erros, se você quer certeza jogue de meta calabreso.

Enfim, partindo para outros pontos cruciais desse deck, pq não 2 Beyond the Pendulum? Se você combou amegan, não tem mais o que buscar no deck kkkk usa a Exceed the Pendulum e puxe o que você precisa do extra deck. "Ai, mas e se eu combei e tomei interação e perdi a Beyond the Pendulum antes de usar?!" Aí você chora, porque mesmo com outra dela no extra deck você não vai ter muito mais o que fazer meu rei, você já vai estar mais pra Nárnia do que qualquer outra coisa.

Continuando, nunca, em hipótese alguma tire a Performapal Celestial Magician do deck, chegar na GranSolfachord Coolia é a coisa mais fácil do mundo e ela previne que os efeitos dos seus pendulum sejam negados, mesmo que a Harmonizing Magician diga o contrário. (Por isso também tem o Supreme King Z-ARC nesse deck, remoção de tudo do campo do oponente e um bicho de 4000 de atk kkkkk).

Solfachord Harmonia, outra coisa que eu recomendo não mexer na quantidade, o que esse campo salva a sua vida quando você só tem a DoSolfachord Cutia e mais alguém no campo é uma brincadeira. Lembre-se sempre que se você voltar a DoSolfachord Cutia do extra deck para a mão, você não vai precisar procurar ela com a Beyond the Pendulum e vai buscar a Harmonizing Magician no lugar dela, melhorando a eficiência do seu turno.

Vou me abster de explicar combos aqui para não fazer essa descrição se tornar (mais ainda) uma bíblia, mas mantenha em mente que (por mais que eu seja apaixonado nesse deck) as Solfachords não são o arquétipo mais forte do jogo, mas conseguem sim lutar de igual contra muita coisa, então eu recomendo muito treinar, principalmente combos curtos e lembrar sempre que a GranSolfachord Coolia é um omni negate que normalmente puxa uma "Ghost Ogre" com mais de 2000 de atk e inegável para o campo kkkk.

Outro ponto importante, como o meta de Fire King já é realidade, pode ser interessante trocar a trap das Solfachords, tirar a Solfachord Musica e colocar a Solfachord Formal , para proteger as suas scales e manter o efeito da GranSolfachord Coolia ativo, ele é o pilar que sustenta esse deck, sem esse efeito você até consegue "jogar", mas com ele ativo você passa de um deck tentando fazer algo para um deck FAZENDO algo.

Eu particularmente gosto de rodar o deck com 2 Trap Trick, porque mesmo que a Soul of the Supreme King venha na mão, ou já esteja morta, você consegue puxar a Infinite Impermanence direto do deck, atenção para o fato de que o efeito dela de limitação de traps entra em efeito após a sua resolução.

O side deck, bem, isso vai depender do seu meta local ou do meta do meio em que você joga, essa parte não tem muita regra, então por favor se aventure testando techs diferentes.

One for One também é questionável o uso, mas ter 4 DoSolfachord Cutia normalmente é mais uma vantagem do que uma desvantagem, então é outro ponto que vale o teste e veja o que se encaixa melhor dentro do teu gosto pessoal.

"Ah, mas o deck é muito frágil contra handtrap!" Sim, não tem muito o que dizer sobre isso além de sim kkkk nenhuma versão dele é particularmente resiliente contra handtrap, "Ah, mas não sei quem fez um deck que passa por cima de 5 handtrap, faz 7 negações e mais 10 interações." Parabéns, eu também consigo fazer isso se eu puxasse sempre uma mão perfeita kkkkk não se enganem com essas promessas de deck perfeito, quando o deck faz tanta coisa assim ele é meta, não um arquétipo quase esquecido kkkkkk.

Uma última coisa, com a presença do Kashtira Fenrir no deck, se acostume a fazer normal summon da SolSolfachord Gracia , isso vai salvar muito combo seu kkkkk.

Enfim, as Solfachords se tornaram uma verdadeira paixão para mim, elas são muito boas e verdadeiramente muito capazes de resultados bons, bastando apenas paciência e muito treino pra entender como a estratégia funciona e como contornar alguns obstáculos. No mais, é um deck muito divertido de se jogar e muito tranquilo de pegar o jeito, também recomendo fortemente jogar e adaptar tudo ao gosto pessoal de vocês, deck que não é meta é além de tudo um reflexo do seu jeito de jogar e pensar, então por favor, aventure-se um pouco mais meu nobre e minha nobre.

É isso, paz! ^0^

deck_excerpt: Virus Lock Deck ft. Soul Drain + Tyrant's Tantrum
deck_description:
Hey there! Some time ago, I made a Virus Deck, where I relived the moments of "Doom Virus Dragon" and "Crush Card Virus". These cards are what Seto Kaiba used in "Waking the Dragons" arc in Duel Monsters anime of Yu-Gi-Oh. So, I decided to get serious and unleash their full potential.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, Special Summon Fusion Parasite while having another Spellcaster monster present...

  • If Parasite is in GY due to Ravenous/Dugares, use "Monster Reborn".
  • If Parasite is in your hand, use Saryuja.

2) Fusion Summon The Dark Magicians (TDM) by using Parasite + Spellcaster as materials. Then, either empty your deck and shuffle "Soul Drain" + "Tyrant's Tantrum" with "The Humble Sentry" or arrange your Main Deck in a way that you would draw them for certain with Saryuja, which is possible when you activate Saryuja if you have 4 cards in Main Deck and you can place 3 cards on the bottom of your Main Deck in any order.

3) Activate TDM to draw these Traps mentioned in #2 and activate them. Since the ability of TDM isn't hard-once per turn, you can reset TDM by destroying with "Offerings to the Doomed" and reviving with "Monster Reborn".

4) Since you know how to reset TDM, do the same for "Eradicator Epidemic Virus" + "Crush Card Virus" + "Deck Devastation Virus" by shuffling them with "The Humble Sentry" and drawing them afterwards with TDM to activate them. Target TDM for EEV + DDV and Exodia/Idol/Parasite for CCV. All three viruses will be active for three turns to detonate whatever your opponent has.

5) In case you miss what is going on, let me brief...

  • Eradicator Epidemic Virus: Destroys Spell and Trap cards of your opponent.
  • Deck Devastation Virus + Crush Card Virus: Destroys Monster cards of your opponent. DDV covers <=1500 ATK while CCV covers >=1500 ATK, that's why.
  • Soul Drain: Monsters that are in GY/BZ can't be activated, which is why you had to play DDV + CCV.
  • Tyrant's Tantrum: Your opponent can't activate Spells from anywhere unless they send 1 Spell from Main Deck to GY. However, with ME-PSY-YA, any Spell and Trap cards are going to be delivered to BZ instead of GY. Therefore, your opponent can't use Spells. Shame there is no Trap counterpart of Tantrum, oh well.

6) Revive beefy monsters with "Monster Reborn" and end your turn. Don't forget to set "Primal Seed", in case you want to continue the loop for some reason.

7) With the effects of EEV + DDV + CCV active, your opponent can't play anything because whatever they draw for 3 turns will be destroyed thanks to virus cards. Nor they can activate Monster effects from GY/BZ and Spells from anywhere. Trap is their only option to save but it's very unlikely to find the out. So, they will have nothing but to pass the turn back to you.

8) Attack the opponent with all you have and victory shall be yours!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial. What a good start to save 30 UR!

- "The Dark Magicians" can be collected by purchasing "Vortex of Magic" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Deck Devastation Virus" + "Eradicator Epidemic Virus" can be found within "Rulers of Darkness" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Primal Seed" + "Fusion Parasite" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Tyrant's Tantrum" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 120 SR and 60 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 660 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

My Fourth Real Life Deck

An updated deck for the ninja archtype:

Decided it was time for an updated deck as there have been a few reprints within the TCG making some cards more affordable.

Strengths:

  • Ninjas are great at filling a board with monsters, allowing for extensive fusions from the archtype or outside with generic fusions.
  • While certain handtraps will brick this deck, it is very possible to play through certain ones such as Ash Blossom.
  • Ninjas are great at reycling cards from the graveyard. This can be done through Notebook of Mystery and Baku as they both can retrieve any ninja card from the grave including each other.
  • Lord of the Heavenly Prison is crucial for this deck. Protecting back row and having a generic search for any spell or trap call allow for extensive plays.

Weaknesses:

  • Ninjas as an archtype isn't splashable what-so-ever. Wont work with other archtypes that well.
  • Using any extra deck monsters that aren't ninja or generic becomes increasingly difficult due to stated above.
  • Hand traps determine turns, especially with the starting hand.
  • No Ninja Tuners :(

Things to Note:

  • Grandmaster Hanzo and Kagero are both the optimal starters as they allow for a search or special summon from the hand.
  • Lord of the Heavenly Prison as stated before issues back row protection, allowing for protection of continuous traps.
  • Saizo should be used for effect to search an Ninjitsu Art card then linked off immediatly.
  • Baku becomes extra useful once 2 or 3 Notebooks of Mystery are used, he allows for the recovery of them which then allows for seemingly infinite resources from grave.
  • Pot of Prosperity for consistency (add as many copies as you'd like).
  • If there is trouble keeping resources during longer games, Pot of Avarice can allow for great card draw and more deck resources.
  • Side deck is of course meta dependent, create at will.

Good Luck!
Gen 3
This is a deck inspired by both the anime and the legacy of duelists pack, which will be able to take advantage of the opponent swiftly.

deck_excerpt: Making Hot Red Abyss in Prediction Princess is a nightmare
deck_description:
The thing about Red Dragon Archfiend and Resonator as two archetypes supporting each other is that Resonator has so many cards that just allow you to turbo out practically any of your Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monsters that you may be playing in your Extra Deck. But because they are able to do this so easily, they have restrictions like locking you into Synchros or locking you into DARK Dragon Synchros. Because of that, it is not that easy to make a Red Dragon Archfiend Prediction Princess Deck. Red Dragon Archfiend has 1 Level 9 monster in Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss which is a Level 9 DARK Dragon Synchro Monster that requires a Tuner monster and a non-Tuner DARK Dragon Synchro Monster as material. As a Quick Effect, you can target a face-up card your opponent controls and negate its effects until the end of the turn. And if it inflicts battle damage to your opponent, you can target a Tuner in your GY and Special Summon it in Defense Position. Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss is a really good form of interruption and negation as it is a proactive effect rather than a reactive effect which allows you to negate cards on field even if your opponent attempts to Chain Block their activations. Because of this, I really wanted to find a way to get to Abyss, target it with World Legacy Monstrosity to get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and another Level 9 out from the Deck, use Abyss and a Level 9 to do the Aggregator line, and then Special Summon back Abyss from GY to use as interruption/protection on the opponent's turn with its effect. There are a couple of ways that we can achieve this: World Legacy Succession, Nine-Lives Cat, or Cloudcastle. But I just find trying to make Nine-Lives Cat or Cloudcastle in addition to the other things we must do as too much to ask for. We already have a enormous combo line that we have to go through to get to Abyss itself, and we can't really maneuver our way to Cat or Cloudcastle that easily. Succession works best after those two other options, but at the same time, I decided that would be only the case if we manage to draw Succession. Doing it everytime is also a bit much to ask (or that's at least what I figure), so we will bring back Abyss with Succession if we do have the Succession only. Next issue I had to address was the Synchro Material requirements. Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss's Synchro Material requirements are not as generic as compared to Crystron Quariongandrax or Crystron Phoenix, so I had to find a way that made it easy on myself and was able to be incorporated into our main combo lines of our Red Resonator Predaplant engine. At first, I tried using Diabellstar the Black Witch and Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye to get both Diabellstar and a copy of Jet Synchron onto the field. That's because Diabellstar is a 7 and Jet is a Level 1 who can Synchro into a DARK Dragon Synchro like Scarred Red Dragon Archfiend, and then Jet can bring itself back to Synchro with that DARK Dragon Synchro to make Abyss. That did work, but it required you to draw Diabellstar access in addition to your Red Resonator Predaplant engine because Diabellstar and Jet would get you Abyss while Red Resonator and the Predaplants would get you to Monstrosity through Ib. So I scrapped that and ended with this. It is similar in concept to our combo for Power Tool Braver Dragon Prediction Princess in using Ultra Polymerization to make Predaplant Ambulomelides who can search for Predapruning and while also being able to make Ultimaya Tzolkin with Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Except, Ib would then float into World Chalice Guardragon while you can set Predapruning to trigger Tzolkin for Scarred Dragon Archfiend. Flip Predapruning for Melides from GY and Tribute it for Tuner 6 access in Predaplant Banksiogre to go into Shooting Riser Dragon with WC Guardragon, and use it to send a 6 from Deck to make it a Tuner 1 to Synchro with Scarred to make Abyss with Monstrosity Access. 2.5-card combo as per usual: Red Resonator, Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, and a monster to send to GY. Normal Red Resonator and Special Scorpio. Scorpio sends a monster from hand to GY to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra searches Ultra Poly. Pay 2000 with Ultra Poly to Fuse Cobra and Scorpio into Ambulomelides. Ambulo adds Predapruning from Deck to hand on Fusion Summon. Banish Ultra Poly from GY targeting Ambulo to bring back Cobra and Scorpio from GY. Synchro Red Resonator and Cobra into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Ib adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Send Ib and Ambulo to GY to Special Summon Tzolkin from Deck. Ib triggers in GY to Special Summon World Chalice Guardragon from Deck. Set Predapruning. Tzolkin triggers to Special Summon Scarred Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck. Flip Predapruning to Special Summon back and equip Ambulomelides from GY.  Ambulo targets and Tributes itself to Special Summon Predaplant Banksiogre from Deck. Synchro Banksiogre and Guardragon into Shooting Riser Dragon. Shooting Riser sends a Bystial from Deck to Gy to make itself a Level 1. Synchro your Level 1 Shooting Riser and your Level 8 Scarred Dragon Archfiend to go into Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. Scarred Dragon Archfiend triggers to Special Summon Red Dragon Archfiend from Extra Deck into the EMZ. Activate Monstrosity targeting Abyss for Bibliomuse and Deus-X from Deck. Link Tzolkin and RDA into I:P Masquerena. Xyz Abyss and Deus-X into Mereologic Aggregator and use its effect to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY which triggers Herald to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Detach Deus-X from Aggregator and reattach Herald from GY to Aggregator. Link Aggregator and Scorpio into Sky Striker Ace - Camellia. Herald Triggers again to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. And it is the usual Prediction Princess combo from here. Is this a good Deck? Not really. You have a couple of bricks in the Deck that you really do not want to draw, and while it is a 2.5-card combo to achieve all of this, you don't really end on anything that has to do with RDA. Do you need to play Tzolkin? I would recommend it because it is difficult to find a way to make both Ib and a DARK Dragon Synchro for Abyss without it. Do you need to actually play Scarred Dragon Archfiend and Red Dragon Archfiend? No. If anything, it just thematically goes better with Abyss and helps to give you more Link Material. You can definitely just play Hundred Eyes Dragon and be done with it, and you could possibly even do something cool with Hundred Eyes if possible (haven't tested it though). Can you actually end on Abyss? Yes, you could through utilizing Succession like I described earlier, or if you already drew Bibliomuse, you can use the Bibliomuse and the Deus-X you got off of Monstrosity to go into Aggregator instead of using Abyss so that you can keep it as a part of your endboard. Reminder that this is just me experimenting with Level 9’s, so don’t actually play this. It is really bad. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Predaplant Banksiogre which is just a Level 6 Tuner we can get from Deck. But it does have a mandatory effect that activates when it leaves the field to place Predator Counters on your opponent's monsters, so it is important to remember that. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio which sends a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck except itself. 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra which adds a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from Deck to hand if Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster once per Duel. 2 Lonefire Blossom which tributes a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Red Resonator which Special Summons a Level 4 or lower monster from hand on Normal Summon and on Special Summon, it can target a face-up monster on field to have you gain LP equal to that monster's ATK. 1 World Legacy Guardragon which is a Level 1 monster that we can Special Summon off of Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. 1 Bystial Magnamhut and 1 Bystial Druiswurm which are Level 6 monsters we can send from Deck for Shooting Riser and they double as interruptions as well. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 1 Ultra Polymerization which Fusion Summons using 2 monsters you control by paying 2000 LP and this activation cannot be responded to by either player. You can also banish it from Gy and target a Fusion Monster that was Summoned by its effect to Special Summon all of the Fusion Material Monsters from your GY with their effects negated and ATK/DEF reduced to 0. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from your hand or you can target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. You could play just the 1 copy, but I am playing 2 to have an increased chance of drawing it so that in a situation where I do draw it, I can instead search for Succession off of Ib to bring back Hot Red Abyss and use it as interruption. 1 World Legacy Succession which targets a monster in your Gy and Special Summons it to Linkpoint. 3 Resonator Call which adds a Resonator monster from Deck to hand. 1 Predapruning which targets and Special Summons a Predaplant monster from your GY and equips this card to it. And 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from your hand or Gy face-up or face-down and you can banish it from Gy during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which adds a Predap card on Fusion Summon and can target and Tribute a monster to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from your Deck. 1 Ultimaya Tzolkin which cannot be Synchro Summoned and can only be Special Summoned from Extra Deck by sending 2 Level 5 or higher monsters you control with the same Level including a Tuner and a non-Tuner to the GY. As a soft once per turn, when a Spell/Trap(s) is set on your field, you can Special Summon a Power Tool Synchro Monster or a Level 7 or 8 Dragon Synchro Monster from your Extra Deck. The monster we are using Tzolkin to get is Scarred Dragon Archfiend, but if you want more Extra Deck space, you can play Hundred Eyes Dragon instead so that you can cut Scarred and regular RDA. Also, maybe you could do something interesting with Hundred Eyes's copying effect. 1 Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss. 1 Scarred Dragon Archfiend which we are using as our DARK Dragon Synchro Monster of choice to Synchro for Abyss. And if it is sent from the Monster Zone to the Gy, you can Special Summon the regular RDA from Extra Deck which gives us more Link Material. Speaking of, the 1 Red Dragon Archfiend for the effect of Scarred. 1 Shooting Riser Dragon which is a Level 7 Synchro Tuner that can send a monster with a lower Level than it from Deck to Gy to reduce its Level by the Level of the sent monster. We are using Shooting Riser as a way to access a Level 1 Tuner. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon and if it leaves the field, you can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from Deck. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if sent to GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia, 1 S:P Little Knight, and 1 I:P Masquerena.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Creator: Marcelo Leon

Tournament: Cochabamba WCQ Regional – January 20th 2024

Placement: 2nd Place

I will be completely honest when I say that the POTE Gem-Knight support was really not it. If anything, it tried to recreate Brilliant Fusion while also turning the Deck into a going second OTK strategy. I'm not against it, but the cards that Gem-Knight got really did not help the Deck at all, even if they intended to make the Deck shift towards going second. The Deck would have a rough time trying to break boards with anything in-archetype or in-engine. Gem-Knight Quartz and Scatter Fusion put the Deck into a situation where it would be highly dependent on going second or going through Black Garden shenanigans to potentially (hypothetically) FTK. Their new Fusion Monster in Gem-Knight Lady Rose Diamond really only is able to do anything on your opponent's turn, and even making it going first for your opponent's turn really doesn't do much, if anything at all, with the effects that it is able to provide. The only card I see having the most potential would be Brilliant Rose as it can Summon itself from hand (as opposed to Crystal Rose Summoning itself from GY) and can send a Gem-Knight or Melodius from Extra Deck to GY to copy some aspect of the sent mosnter (as opposed to Crystal Rose sending from Deck). Gem-Knight has 1 Level 9 monster in Gem-Knight Master Diamond who is a Level 9 EARTH Rock Fusion Monster that requires 3 Gem-Knight monsters as Fusion Material. It gains 100 ATK for each Gem- monster in your GY and as a soft once per turn, it can banish a Level 7 or lower Gem-Knight Fusion Monster from your GY and until the End Phase, Master Diamond's name becomes that monster's name and this effect is replaced with that monster's effects. Addressing the elephant in the room, Master Diamond is an EARTH monster, so we cannot get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse out from the Deck if we target Master Diamond with World Legacy Monstrosity. And besides, if we did a Monstrosity line for a Rank 9, we won't be able to make use of Master Diamond's effect. Let's try something different today. Galaxy Queen's Light is a card that I am very familiar with since my friends used to use it all the time in their Decks when we played together. Can't remember if it was for Trains, Blue-Eyes, or Red-Eyes, but I have had experience seeing this card in action. It targets a Level 7 or higher monster you control to have the Levels of all other face-up monsters you currently control become the current Level of that monster. This card looks crazy in Fortune Lady, but we are going to be using this card to get ourselves 2 Level 9's on the field to go into Mereologic Aggregator. So, how are we gonna search it? PHHY gave us Galaxy Photon Dragon which is a generic Rank 4 that can detach a material to either add or send to GY, a Photon or Galaxy card from Deck. We are very capable of making a Rank 4 in this Deck. To do this, we need a hand of Gem-Armadillo, Brilliant Rose, and a way to get a Gem-Knight Normal Monster onto the field. When it comes to Brilliant Rose, you don't need to open it per say since there are plenty of ways to help us get to where we need to go, but we are going to be using this 3-card combo as an example. Let's say that our way of accessing a Normal Gem-Knight is Unexpected Dai. Activate Dai to get Gem-Knight Tourmaline from Deck onto the field (I like Tourmaline the best, but it can be any Level 4 Normal Monster Gem-Knight). Normal Gem-Armadillo and activate its effect to search for any Gem-Knight monster you want. Doesn't really matter what you get with this opening hand consisting of Unexpected Dai. Activate Brilliant Rose sending the Gem-Knight you searched to GY to Special Rose from hand. Activate Rose's other effect to send Gem-Knight Seraphinite from Extra Deck to GY. Link Tourmaline and Brilliant Rose into Gem-Knight Phantom Quartz. Phantom Quartz adds another Tourmaline from Deck to hand. You just need to search for a Level 4 Gem-Knight here and Tourmaline is the only one we have in the Deck. Pay 1000 LP with Phantom Quartz to Fusion Summon Gem-Knight Lady Brilliant Diamond by shuffling Tourmaline, the Gem-Knight you discarded, and Brilliant Rose (because it is always treated as a Gem-Knight) into the Deck. Lady Brilliant Diamond uses her effect to send Phantom Quartz to GY to Special Summon Gem-Knight Master Diamond from Extra Deck ignoring its Summoning Conditions. Activate Master Diamond's effect to banish and copy Seraphinite's effect from GY. Now, you have an extra Normal Summon of any monster. Normal Summon that Tourmaline you searched. Now you have 2 Level 4's on field in Gem-Armadillo and Gem-Knight Tourmaline. Xyz them into Galaxy Photon Dragon and detach 1 to search for Galaxy Queen's Light. Activate GQL targeting Master Diamond which turns Lady Brilliant Diamond into your second Level 9 monster. Now, you have Rank 9 access and can make Mereologic Aggregator. Aggregator and Herald will be able to add 2 Ritual Monster/Spell cards from Deck to hand. But that doesn't mean that you have enough for your Prediction Princess plays unless you hard drew Bibliomuse. Well, to help out in that aspect, we are playing the second copy of Tarotreith along with 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites, so as long as you see at least 1 Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell in your opener, you basically have full Prediction Princess combo right then and there. And even if you don't have Bibliomuse, Underworld Ritual and grab it from Deck and put it onto the field and make its search effect available on your opponent's turn. I don't hate this Deck. Not every single one of my Prediction Princess Decks that focus on a Level 9 EARTH monster have access to a Rank 4 which is a letdown, but it does allow for you to play a pretty cool card in Galaxy Queen's Light in Gem-Knight Prediction Princess specifically. Do I think that this Deck is good? Not really. It is not like Gem-Knight is actually doing anything for you other than forcing you to take alternate routes to get to where you need to go. It is certainly playable and more so than some of my other Prediction Princess variants, but I'd prefer a different brew to this. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Traotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 3 Gem-Knight Tourmaline which is just my favorite Gem-Knight Normal Monster, but you can play any Level 4 Gem-Knight Normal Monster. 3 Gem-Armadillo which adds a Gem-Knight monster from Deck to hand on Normal Summon. 2 Gem-Knight Obsidian which targets a Level 4 or lower Normal Monster in your Gy and Special Summons it if it is sent from hand to GY. This is your way of getting a Normal Gem-Knight monster onto the field if you have Painful Decision. Painful sends a Tourmaline from Deck to Gy and adds another one from Deck to hand. Normal Gem-Armadillo and searches for Brilliant Rose or Obsidian (whichever you don't have). Brilliant Rose discards Obsidian to Summon itself and Obsidian Special Summons the Tourmaline from GY. 3 Brilliant Rose which is always treated as a Gem-Knight card and can discard a Gem-Knight or Melodius card to Special Summon itself from hand. And as a soft once per turn, it can send a Gem-Knight or Melodius monster from Extra Deck to GY to make its name/Type/Attribute become the same as the sent monster's until the End Phase.

Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which specifically Ritual Summons Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except during the turn it was sent there in order to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Painful Decision, 3 Unexpected Dai, and 1 Galaxy Queen's Light.

Extra Deck: 1 Gem-Knight Lady Brilliant Diamond which needs 3 Gem-Knight monsters to Fusion Summon it and you can only Special Summon her once per turn. And she can send a face-up Gem-Knight monster you control to Special Summon a Gem-Knight Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck ignoring its Summoning Conditions. 1 Gem-Knight Master Diamond. 1 Gem-Knight Seraphinite which we are just sending off of Brilliant Rose to copy its effect with Master Diamond. It lets you have an extra Normal Summon during your Main Phase. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck if sent to GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Galaxy Photon Dragon. 1 Gem-Knight Phantom Quartz which needs 2 Gem- monsters as Link Material and if it is Link Sumoned, you can add a Gem-Knight card from Deck to hand. And it can pay 1000 LP to Fusion Summon a Gem-Knight Fusion Monster from Extra Deck by shuffling materials from your Gy or that are banished into the Deck but that monster cannot attack directly this turn. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. And 1 Gravity Controller.

deck_description:
The official Yu-Gi-Oh Banlist applies to this format. 

Altered Rules: 

1. Fusion, Xyz, Synchro, Link, and Pendulum Monsters can only be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck to an Extra Monster Zone, or a Main Monster Zone a Link Monster Points to. 

2. The turn player can only use one Extra Monster Zone per turn. Once they have used one, they cannot use the other one until the end of their turn. 

3. The turn player can conduct two Normal Summons/Sets; one in Main Phase 1, and one in Main Phase 2. 

4. The first turn player does not skip their draw during the first Draw Phase. 

5. Main deck limit is 40 to 50 cards. 

6. Extra Deck and Side Deck limit is 10. 

7. Players can only use one card per copy in their Main and Extra Deck with exceptions based on choosing one of the following builds (non-effect monsters do not count against this limit): 

- You can have one Forbidden Card in your deck, as well as 2 or 3 copies of one card of your choosing. 

- You can have 3 copies of two cards of your choosing. 

- You can have 2 copies of three cards of your choosing.

Behold, Summoned Skull Beatdown in 2024! This deck focuses on summoning Summoned Skull and keeping it on board with the Labrynth cards.

Labrynth Labyrinth is a very useful field spell to revive fiends off the use of a non-labrynth normal spell. Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch and Archfiend's Roar are perfect for this, particularly as they both trigger Labrynth effects.

Fists of the Unrivalved Tenyi is also a great counter trap that we can search by milling Heavenly Dragon Circle with Foolish Burial Goods. And if that set trap happens to get destroyed then you get to float into powerful extra deck monsters such as Black Skull Dragon and Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon.

Disruptions:

Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch to pop + mill Farfa for a banish.

Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi - omni negate

Labrynth Labyrinth - extra pop through Welcome Labrynth

Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle - field or hand pop

Big Welcome Labrynth GY effect - bounce cards

Tour Bus from the Underworld - GY disruption

Dogmatika Punishment - pop + extra deck card effect (e.g. N'tss pop)

This is very much a slow and steady style deck rather than a combo heavy deck. Use the Labrynth cards to recycle and search your traps, and then keep Summoned Skull on the field to attack for game!
Blue-Eyes Deck for Tcg 2024

deck_excerpt: Wake up, Summoned Skull, we have a city to burn!
deck_description:
Archfiend's Awakening is a fairly decent wall in the sense that it can't really be destroyed except for against other Ritual monsters. This deck uses Dogmatika cards to search out all the necessary cards you need in order to summon Archfiend's Awakening. By milling Herald of the Arc Lights, you can search cards such as Dogmatikalamity and Dogmatika Maximus to not only send even more extra deck monsters, but to bring the likes of Advanced Ritual Art to your hand.

Alba Zoa is an alternate boss monster of the deck. Really the main disruptions are Extra Deck mills, pops from Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch and Dogmatika Punishment, and a pseudo D-Barrier lock with Simul Archfiends. You can also lock Special Summoning into DARK via Barrier Statue of the Abyss.

Have fun!

This is a synchro variant for Summoned Skull! It uses two primary lines: Quick Launch, which is a 1 card Archfiend's Call, and Emergency Teleport, which is effectively a 1.5 card Archfiend's Call. Summoning up to two untargetable Archfiend Calls could be useful, particularly when paired with one or more Falling Downs, so that you can steal all your opponent's strongest monsters! The Fallen of Albaz cards provide some extra power, not only via Mirrorjade, but also to help set up Chaos Archfiend. Rindbrumm sets up Chaos Archfiend on the following turn, which is very strong.

The fusion variant of Summoned Skull is pretty versatile. There's a number of cards that discard for effect which helps you net more Heiress searches, and thanks to cards like Edge-Imp Sabres, you can "Oath stack" which means you use Archfiend's Oath to either draw back into what you put, or you call it wrong intentionally to trigger effects (e.g. stack an Heiress and mill it for a search). Branded Fusion is a 1 card Archfiend's Manifestation and thanks to the added power of the other Branded cards, your Summoned Skull will have plenty of backup. The deck also uses Archfiend Black Skull Dragon as an alternate win condition to burn for game, in addition to Chaos Archfiend. The Eccelsias paired with Fallen of Albaz and Rindbrumm all set up a Chaos Archfiend play.

This variant focuses on XYZ summoning Archfiend's Ascent. It uses various means to get you there, including a combination of Shadow's Light and Duality (which, in turn, also enable Chaos Archfiend). Thanks to Masterking Archfiend, you can also take advantage of 1000LP payment cards such as Ready Fusion, to not only summon Soul Hunter, but mill other material such as Angmarl the Fiendish Monarch, or disrupt the opponent by milling Farfa. It's quite a quirky all or nothing style deck, but if you like Archfiend's Ascent then give this a go.

This variant of Summoned Skull attempts to summon as many different types of Summoned Skull as possible. The synchro and ritual variants will be two of the easier and more useful ones. The synchro is fairly easy to summon using Quick Launch as it is a 1 card Archfiend's Call. My suggestion is to make all your extra deck plays in the first half of your combo, and bring out as much as you can, then, if you either get disrupted or run out of gas, start using the Dogmatika cards to bring out Archfiend's Awakening. Not only will this net you extra bodies, but also disrupt the opponent's extra deck as well, potentially milling crucial combo pieces. White Relic is a decent piece of disruption in this regard, as is Maximus, all the while the different Summoned Skull variants are walling up to float at a moment's notice.

Branded in High Spirits discards for effect, which is nice to trigger Archfiend Heiress, and the Ecclesias paired with Fallen of Albaz and Rindbrumm enable Chaos Archfiend, an alternate win condition that can attack everything for 4500 ATK each, and if it leaves the field it gets to float into Chaos Angel!

Other disruptions include Archfiend's Ghastly Glitch for a pop + banish by milling Farfa.

Blind second Despian Dogmatika deck

Blackwings are one of the premier deck types of Edison Format. This variant focuses on draw power. Everyone knows Black Whirlwind can be an automatic "I win" button, doubly so if you draw both of them, so this deck emphasizes your ability to gain access to them. The deck features a whopping 6 draw cards which aid in consistency by letting you more quickly and reliably get to the best cards the deck has to offer.

 

"Why 2 Upstart Goblins instead of 3?" Deck space is tight and you don't wanna give your opponent too much free lifepoints.

 

"Why is Fissure in the side deck rather than Smashing Ground?" I'm glad you asked! Fissure destroys the weakest monster, which is specifically advantageous in countering Consecrated Light.

 

"Why is Starlight Road in the side deck?" You don't really need to use it in the main deck because you can bait out Heavy Storm with Legacy of Yata-Garasu and Solemn Judgment. Starlight Road is good in certain match-ups, such as the mirror match, Lightsworns, and Quickdraw.

 

Fun fact: you can use D.D. Crow as Icarus Attack fodder.

deck_excerpt: "Are you the lore protagonist because you're Visas or are you Visas because you're the lore protagonist?"
deck_description:
"Are you the lore protagonist because you're Visas or are you Visas because you're the lore protagonist?"

 

The second wave of Mannadium cards in Masterduel has arrived, and the strategy is almost at full power! With merely 1-2 cards, combo off into unbreakable set-ups and smash through established boards!

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

Visas Amritara (searches any card with his name) and Trisukta (Enables 1 card combos makes Mannadium more resilient to interruption, less bricky and incredibly powerful. Since consistency has been turned up a notch, there is more room for staples so that you can come out on top of the ever annoying "Maxx C" minigame. You can also fit more handtraps to weaken opposing decks you can combo off in your own turn!

 

The strength of Mannadium that separates it from other combo decks comes from it's natural ability to smash through established boards with in-engine cards like Vicious Astraloud, Planet Reichphobia, Baronne De Fleur and Accesscode. Combined with a critical mass of handtraps and boardbreakers, Mannadium can play through any strategy!

 

 As a result, the Mannadium strategy of summoning a lot of negate-oriented boss monsters turn 1 is has been thoroughly streamlined and made much easier. 

If you want a thorough guide with combos on how to pilot this deck, check out my earlier article. 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Yata-Garasu Lock ft. Miracle Locus + Disturbance Strategy + Droll
deck_description:
Hello there, whatsup? About a week ago, I made a Yata-Lock deck and I decided to do another version. Let's have a look!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw until you find these combo pieces: Yata-Garasu + Droll + Miracle Locus + Disturbance Strategy. Then, set Disturbance + Miracle and end your turn but not before changing the button at the lower right corner of the screen to "ON". You don't want to miss anything happening, do you?

2) During your opponent's Standby Phase, activate Miracle to let your opponent draw a card. Then, activate Disturbance and chain into Droll. What will happen is Droll denies for either side to add any card to their hand. Therefore, by shuffling your opponent's hand into deck with Disturbance, they won't be able to draw/add any card afterwards, all thanks to Droll.

3) If you go first, your opponent has nothing to do but pass the turn back to you. When it's your turn, destroy "Chicken Game" if present and Normal Summon Yata-Garasu. Attack the opponent with everything you got. If the opponent is still alive, Yata denies your opponent from drawing any card.

4) Your opponent is stuck, again. Just keep attacking your opponent until they die.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Mannadium Trisukta" can be found within "Indomitable Pride" Timed Pack to save 30 SR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 450 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Read description for information on the casual fan-made Reborn Format.
deck_description:
The official Yu-Gi-Oh Banlist applies to this format. 

Altered Rules: 

1. Fusion, Xyz, Synchro, Link, and Pendulum Monsters can only be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck to an Extra Monster Zone, or a Main Monster Zone a Link Monster Points to. 

2. The turn player can only use one Extra Monster Zone per turn. Once they have used one, they cannot use the other one until the end of their turn. 

3. The turn player can conduct two Normal Summons/Sets; one in Main Phase 1, and one in Main Phase 2. 

4. The first turn player does not skip their draw during the first Draw Phase. 

5. Main deck limit is 40 to 50 cards. 

6. Extra Deck and Side Deck limit is 10. 

7. Players can only use one card per copy in their Main and Extra Deck with exceptions based on choosing one of the following builds (non-effect monsters do not count against this limit): 

- You can have one Forbidden Card in your deck, as well as 2 or 3 copies of one card of your choosing. 

- You can have 3 copies of two cards of your choosing. 

- You can have 2 copies of three cards of your choosing.

047 - Machina Mayhem Structure Deck

Hey there! In this deck, we will back and forth the burn between Lazion and Lantron, ultimately leading to your opponent and meeting their demise. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, plant at least two flowers to opposing side with "Black Garden". Next, discard 2 x Lazion with Ravenous. Then, Special Summon Lantron with Saryuja.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

3) Revive 2 x Lazion with "Monster Reborn" and pass them to opposing side by replacing flowers with "Mystic Box". Then, shuffle a card with "Magical Mallet"...

  • What will happen is: Since you draw a card with Mallet, mandatory effect of Lazion activates. There, 2 x Lazion deals 2 x 1000 = 2000 damage to you in total. However, Lantron will reflect said damage right back at your opponent.

4) Since the effect of Lazion isn't hard-once per turn, we can reset them with "Book of Lunar Eclipse" + "Dark-Piercing Light" combination.

5) Repeat what was explained in #4 + #5 until the opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Book of Lunar Eclipse" can be found within "Beastly Claws of Terror" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Don't believe in the judgements of satan!
deck_description:
This is the most manly deck I've ever created. It's so Christian than even satan itself wants me to believe that it is worthless but it's value lies in Christ. The key is appreciating what God has given to us and sharing that with others while reminding others that they don't have to rely on satan or its' judgements to play the game. We are meant to lose life points when our "monsters" accept others' relationship with God and are meant to gain life points when the truths of how God gives life is given to us. Zefras know how to have faith in the God that made them and this must be taken into account when sharing them with others.

Zefranaga was visited by the Holy Spirit through Gabriel so that he may understand how to resist satan manipulating him through how he became Kirkyeon.

Zefracore (formerly Gem-Knight Crystal and was turned into Zefra'ath to help defeat Tierra through Jesus instead of satan) was visited by Jesus fully in order to resist how satan manipulated his body and talents to try to decieve many.

Wen was visited by the angel Haniel (Grace) in order to be able to endure the trial by which she must free others from the shaddoll system via the grace of God.

Pillica was visited by Rapheal in order to remind others of the promises of God and His throne so then the Gustos could be redeemed from their error.

Zefraniu (most likely was Deng Long) was exposed to the angel Tzaphkiel giving it the understanding of the Breath of Life and that it has a soul turning it into an angent for God instead of satan. In retaliation, satan disfigures its' outside.

Zefraxi (used to be Suanni) was exposed to the angel Zadkiel allowing it to understand the love of God and to love God in return distorting satan's original motive for the Yang Zing. In retaliation, satan distorts the outside of Zefraxi to try and have it be misused as tool of war.

Zefrasaber was visited by the angel Metatron allowing for others to see how he and the Nekroz were actually blessed by God to do good in His name instead of honoring satan's plan for them.

Zefraxi (formerly Exa from the Dragunity group) was visited by the angel Michael and so then he could have faith in God and not be bound by the events of the Dragunity and to help others in the name of God instead of just the Nekroz.

Zefraxciton (formerly Exciton Knight) was also visited by Tzaphkiel alerting him of the realities of the Breath of Life within himself so then he can reveal the truth of the hidden things to others so people could understand that no thing is hidden from God.

Zefrathuban was was visited by the glory of God through Gevurah understanding the strength of God and His wrath toward satan so then he can share with others to accept the sovereignty and glory of God and be able to resist satan's temporary benefits.
