deck_excerpt: 42 card Umi Control set to help interrupt the current meta
deck_description:
Since the current banlist took Gozen Match to one, I wanted to find a way to maintain the same level of field lock as before, yet not have to rely on drawing or losing my only copy of Gozen Match. This build has nearly gotten into Top 8 at regionals and YCS tournaments, and is still very underrated and unexpected to play against with the current meta.

This deck has primarily a three card combo lock consisting of Electric Jellyfish, either Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin or Fish Sonar, and Ties of the Brethren to lock your opponent into a single normal summoned monster as well as severely locking their special summoning. This combo also gives you a once-per-turn battle negate and monster destruction alongside the initial lock, allowing for easy damage for game.

 

You can also utilize the XYZ Armor engine to create large monsters and various interruptions for your opponent, the Bahamut/Toad combo for negates, and even the Stealth Kragen to help attribute lock your opponent as well. The addition of AA-Zeus and TY-PHON allow for some much needed extra firepower and defensive strategies. 

Admittedly, I have tried to utilize Link Monsters such as Apollousa, I:P and S:P, Accescode, and others, but with the water attribute lock, it made things unnecessarily difficult to keep that same level of control. I would like to try to add additional negates/interruptions for your opponent's counters, so any constructive criticism/feedback is appreciated.

deck_excerpt: Read description for information on the casual fan-made Reborn Format.
deck_description:
The official Yu-Gi-Oh Banlist applies to this format. 

Altered Rules: 

1. Fusion, Xyz, Synchro, Link, and Pendulum Monsters can only be Special Summoned from the Extra Deck to an Extra Monster Zone, or a Main Monster Zone a Link Monster Points to. 

2. The turn player can only use one Extra Monster Zone per turn. Once they have used one, they cannot use the other one until the end of their turn. 

3. The turn player can conduct two Normal Summons/Sets; one in Main Phase 1, and one in Main Phase 2. 

4. The first turn player does not skip their draw during the first Draw Phase. 

5. Main deck limit is 40 to 50 cards. 

6. Extra Deck and Side Deck limit is 10. 

7. Players can only use one card per copy in their Main and Extra Deck with exceptions based on choosing one of the following builds (non-effect monsters do not count against this limit): 

- You can have one Forbidden Card in your deck, as well as 2 or 3 copies of one card of your choosing. 

- You can have 3 copies of two cards of your choosing. 

- You can have 2 copies of three cards of your choosing.

deck_excerpt: Greed OTK ft. Bistro Butcher + Disturbance Strategy
deck_description:
Hello! In this deck, we will deal damage to the opponent with "Greed" by letting the opponent draw lots of cards with "The Bistro Butcher" and "Disturbance Strategy". Let's see...

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, play "Chain Summoning". Next, plant flowers to opposing side with "Black Garden". Then, play "Burning >>> Broken" combo to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1 with Bamboo Swords.

2) When you have Panda present besides four other monsters, Link Summon Saryuja with these four. Then, Summon these monsters in this order...

  1. Special Summon Bistro with Saryuja.
  2. Tribute Summon Hela by using Saryuja + Panda as materials.
  3. Normal Summon Wanghu.

3) Pass Wanghu to opposing side by replacing a flower with "Mystic Box" and activate "Zombie World". Then, when you have Wattfox in-hand and if you have played "Into the Void" beforehand, set all Traps and end your turn but don't forget to change the button at the lower right corner of the screen to "ON".

4) During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate these cards in order...

  1. Hela >>> Tribute Hela >>> Target Wattfox
  2. Greed + Yang Zing Unleashed

5) So, here is what will happen: Hela Special Summons Wattfox by tributing herself. Even though Wattfox wasn't Zombie monster by default, "Zombie World" changed the outcome in that regard, which was done in #3. Next, Wanghu destroys Wattfox and your opponent will be heavily restricted. Only thing they can do is Normal Summon and Set stuff. As for Unleashed, you will lock your opponent into Battle Phase after their Main Phase 1 has been skipped, which was done in #1.

6) You are in Battle Phase and your opponent can only attack Bistro Butcher with whatever they have. By dealing some Battle Damage, you can let your opponent draw lots of cards. When it's done, activate "Disturbance Strategy" to reshuffle their hand and draw same amount of cards.

7) When you are in Main Phase 2, don't panic. With Wattfox being active, your opponent can't make a big board or use hand-traps. Had it not been the case, during Bistro + Disturbance shenanigans, your opponent would have found a way out and wreck your setup. So, your opponent will eventually run out of moves and end their turn.

8) Remember Greed? When you are in End Phase, Greed calculates how many cards either sides have drawn. Your opponent drew a lot, which would be enough to deal lethal damage.

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

deck_excerpt: Greed FTK ft. Oracle King + Number 43 + Reload
deck_description:

Gameplan

1) At one point, play "Temple >>> Greed" combo . After you have Link Summoned Saryuja, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Black Luster Soldier with his ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Then, banish Saryuja with Black Luster Soldier and Fusion Summon Oracle King right at where Saryuja was, by activating Swirl in-hand and using Swirl + Ghost in-hand as materials.

2) Revive Swirl + Ghost + Exodia/Idol with "Monster Reborn". In order to XYZ Summon Number 43, you need 3 x DARK monsters which are Level 2. So, raise the Level of Exodia/Idol piece by 1 and you are good to go.

3) Draw your deck completely and play "Reload" a lot to shuffle your hand into the deck and draw that many from your deck. Reason is that when you hit End Phase, you would like to take lots of damage incoming from "Greed"...

deck_excerpt: Diabellstar Rescue-ACE  / Hermosillo WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Edgar Rogelio Jaramillo

Tournament: Hermosillo WCQ Regional – January 20th 2024

Placement: Top 8

**Strategy:**

 

1. **Establish Control:** Begin the duel by setting up your lockdown cards. Get "There Can Be Only One" on the field to limit your opponent's monster types. Utilize cards like "Solemn Judgment," "Solemn Strike," and "Metaion, the Timelord" to negate and disrupt your opponent's plays.

 

2. **Kaijus and Lava Golem:** If your opponent manages to establish a threatening board, use Kaijus or Lava Golem to tribute their monsters, breaking their setup. This provides an additional layer of disruption and control.

 

3. **Draw Power:** Use cards like "Pot of Duality" and "Card of Demise" to maintain hand advantage and ensure you have the necessary resources to control the game.

 

4. **Super Polymerization:** Utilize "Super Polymerization" to disrupt your opponent's plays by Fusion Summoning powerful monsters using their monsters as materials. This can be a game-changer, especially against decks that heavily rely on specific monster types.

 

5. **Defense Mechanisms:** Include cards like "Swift Scarecrow," "Waboku," and "Threatening Roar" to protect yourself from direct attacks and buy time to establish your lockdown.

 

6. **Extra Deck Options:** While your lockdown strategy discourages Extra Deck usage, have a few versatile Fusion monsters like "Starving Venom Fusion Dragon" or "Mudragon of the Swamp" that can be summoned with "Super Polymerization" based on the monsters your opponent controls.

 

**Win Condition:**

 

- **Outlast and Chip Away:** The primary win condition is to outlast your opponent by continually disrupting their plays, controlling the field, and preventing them from establishing a threatening board.

 

- **Deck Out:** With cards like "Pot of Duality," "Card of Demise," and minimal special summoning, you may aim to deck your opponent out if the game progresses for an extended period.

 

- **Life Point Advantage:** Over time, as you control the game and your opponent's options, you can secure a life point advantage. Use this advantage to finish off your opponent when the opportunity arises.

 

Remember to adapt your strategy based on the specific decks you face and the evolving metagame. This type of deck requires careful resource management and strategic decision-making. Good luck with your lockdown deck!

deck_excerpt: Down with Amaterasu, Beaufort IX GAMING (supposedly)
deck_description:
This is a bit of a weird one. By all means do not take this Deck seriously because, to be fair, I wasn’t all that serious when I made this Deck. One of the Level 9 monsters we are taking a look at today is Raging Storm Dragon - Beaufort IX which is a Level 9 WIND Dragon Ritual Monster. You can Ritual Summon it using Breath of Acclimation. When an opponent's monster declares a direct attack, you can discard Beaufort to negate the attack and negate that monster's effects. While it is on the field, you can Quick Effect target a face-up monster your opponent controls to return both it and Beaufort to the hand. For a counterpart to Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended, Beaufort IX is really bad in comparison. If we pretend that Voiceless Voice hadn't released yet, Sauravis is still really good in comparison to Beaufort IX because it can discard itself from hand to negate an activated card or effect that targets a monster you control. This is so much better than Beaufort negating a direct attack and negating the attacking monster's effects. Now, if we factor in Voiceless Voice making Sauravis trivial to Summon, Sauravis is now lightyears above Beaufort IX because it is literally Solemn Warning on legs. This is a big difference compared to Beaufort IX bouncing itself and a face-up monster your opponent controls. Also, it is not like Ritual Summoning Beaufort IX is easy either. Breath of Acclimation is just the generic Ritual Spell for WIND Ritual Monsters, and it is not like Beaufort is tied in (or will be tied into) an archetype like Sauravis now is. The only way I can conceivably see it being easily Summoned (aside from Drytrons) is Stars Align Above the Shrine, the Shinobird Field Spell which Ritual Summons a WIND Ritual Monster from Deck. But you can only use Shinobird Tokens and/or Spirit Monsters you control as Ritual fodder. That means that we need to be playing Spirit Monsters now, which leads us into our next Level 9 monster. Amaterasu is a Level 9 LIGHT Fairy Spirit Monster. It cannot be Normal or Special Summoned (BIG RED FLAG) which means that it can only be Tribute Set. During either player's turn when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets Amaterasu while it is face-down, you can change it to face-up Defense Position (on activation, not on resolution) in order to draw 1 card. And if it is flipped face-up, it has a mandatory effect that activates that banishes all other cards on the field. And it returns itself to the hand during the End Phase of the turn it was flipped face-up. Before I get into the card, let's get some rulings correct here. If Amaterasu is targeted by your opponent while face-down, she flips herself face-up in response to the targeting which means she flips herself on activation and draws on resolution. Secondly, because she flips herself face-up on activation of her previous effect, it triggers the mandatory effect to banish the whole field as Chain Link 3 (Chain Link 1 was the targeting and Chain Link 2 is the flip face-up). Dear lord, Amaterasu is a bad card. Like don't get me wrong. Sakitama and Konohanasakuya make Amaterasu a lot easier (to a degree) to Summon. But the biggest offender is that she needs to be Tribute Set and her effect to banish the whole field is mandatory. If we put this into perspective of a Prediction Princess Deck, we can't target her with Monstrosity because she starts off face-down (not like she could actually get Bibliomuse from Deck when targeted by Monstrosity anyways). Also, she's gonna banish our whole field. So why are we even playing her? Well, it is just a consideration. Going back to Stars Align Above the Shrine, getting 9+ Levels of Spirit Monsters onto the field is a lot to ask for just to Ritual Summon Beaufort IX. Because of that, we are playing a lower Level target to Ritual Summon from Deck: Shinobaron Shade Peacock who is just a Level 4. It an Tribute its Ritual Summoned self from field to search for a Spirit Monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck. He's sort of like the Spirit Monster version of Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. So, if we are gonna search for a Spirit Monster, we should at least have a funny target to search which resulted me in deciding on Amaterasu. You could Main Deck Tsumuha-Kutsunagi the Lord of Swords over Amaterasu, but we are siding it (for the lols) and it is overall a much easier to Summon card overall and pretty neat. Again, this is a miserable Deck. The only combo that really worked for me is a 4-card combo to get to both Beaufort IX and full Prediction Princess combo: Stars Align Above the Shrine, Aratama, Konohanasakuya, and World Legacy Monstrosity. Normal Aratama and use it to search for Sakitama. Sakitama effect in hand to immediately Normal Summon itself. Next, you can Special Summon Konohanasakuya from hand since you control a Spirit Monster. Activate Shrine and use its effect to Ritual Summon Beaufort IX from Deck using your whole field. Target it with Monstrosity for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. There you go, full Prediction Princess combo. This Deck is awful and it barely works, but it crosses off Beaufort IX and Amaterasu off of my list of Level 9's in the game.

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Raging Storm Dragon - Beaufort IX. 2 Shinobaron Shade Peacock. 1 Amaterasu. 3 Aratama which is a Level 4 Spirit Monster that adds a Spirit Monster from Deck to hand on Normal Summon. 2 Sakitama which is another Level 4 Spirit Monster which can reveal itself in hand to immediately Normal Summon a Spirit Monster from hand, and if it is Tributed, you can target a Spirit Monster in your GY and add it to your hand. 3 Konohanasakuya which, unlike Spirit Monsters normally, cannot be Normal Summoned/Set and must be Special Summoned from hand by controlling a Spirit Monster as an inherent Summon. It still returns itself to the hand during the End Phase and also during the End Phase, you can banish it from your GY to target a Spirit Monster you control to prevent neither player from activating that face-up monster's effects on the field for the rest of the turn. This is supposed to stop the self-bounce during the End Phase effect of Spirit Monsters. You don't really use this effect in this Deck because none of your Spirit Monsters are really sticking around on field, but it is nice to know and it can even keep Amaterasu on field after it has been flipped face-up if you want.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which specifically Ritual Summons Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except during the turn it was sent there in order to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute but with different names. 1 Terraforming. And 3 Stars Align Above the Shrine which can Ritual Summon a WIND Ritual Monster from your Deck by tributing Shinobird Tokens and/or Spirit Monsters you control as a soft once per turn and up to twice per turn, if a face-up WIND monster(s) you control is returned to the hand, you can add a Spirit Monster or Ritual Spell that is banished or in your GY to your hand or set a Stars Align across the Milky Way. We are only using this card for the Ritual Summoning effect since we aren't keeping any WINDs on field to bounce to hand in one way or another to really make use of those 2 other effects.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Full Armored Utopic Ray Lancer which is a Rank 4 Xyz that can also be made using a Rank 4 or lower Xyz Monster and by discarding a Spell/Trap. It reduces the ATK of all monsters your opponent controls by 500 and once per Battle Phase, you can negate the effects of all face-up Attack Position monsters your opponent controls. If it attacks and destroys an opponent's monster, you can detach a material to have this card make a second attack. I really like this card and I can't wait for it to be released in the TCG (specifically for the Lady of Lament side of my brain). 1 Abyss Dweller. 1 Tornado Dragon. 1 Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 1 Tsumuha-Kutsunagi the Lord of Swords, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Davide Gumeni

Tournament: Foggia WCQ Regional – January 14th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Good day to you! Have you wondered how to burn your opponent to death with Number 30? If you are, let's take a look!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant no more than three flowers to opposing side with "Black Garden". If you got excess, destroy them with Offerings/Baronne. Also, don't forget to destroy Garden with Ancient/Ravenous/Baronne.

2) Special Summon Banisher with Saryuja and Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. With everything being sent to BZ, Ritual Summon Gustkraken by using another Gustkraken as material with Aquamirror. By doing so, you can shuffle whatever your opponent has in their hand to their Main Deck. You can fetch Gustkraken + Aquamirror with "Primal Seed" loop and repeat this step until your opponent has no resources in-hand.

3) Revive two of these monsters with "Monster Reborn", which are Integrator/Martial/Shamisen. Next, XYZ Summon Number 30 by using them as materials and destroy Number 30 with Offerings. Then, return Number 30 + 2 x Level 3 from BZ to GY with Different Dimension, which lets you revive two more Number 30 monsters.

4) When all three Number 30 monsters are in GY, revive them and pass to opposing side by replacing a flower with "Mystic Box". Then, set "Primal Seed" + "Drop Off" and end your turn.

5) When it's your opponent's Draw Phase, activate "Drop Off" to discard whatever they drew to BZ. If you must, negate whatever your opponent can activate in response to "Drop Off" with Baronne. When it's your opponent's Standby Phase, 3 x Number 30 will explode 3 x 2000 = 6000 damage in total to your opponent's face because they have no XYZ materials to detach and prevent the explosion from happening. What's more interesting is...

  • Your opponent can't Special Summon anything, which blocks your opponent's way out with Extra Deck shenanigans to get rid of Number 30 cards.
  • Your opponent can't attack with Number 30 cards because they have no XYZ materials.

6) Your opponent has nothing to do but to pass the turn to you. Just repeat "Drop Off" shenanigans explained in #4 + #5 while your opponent is crushed by three big golems. Victory shall be yours!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Drop Off" + "Primal Seed" + "Number 30" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 150 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Evigishki Gustkraken" can be found within "Rites of the Mirrorworld" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 270 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Flood the field with trap monsters in order to summon the all powerful god of the skies, Slifer the Sky Dragon
deck_description:
Slifer has been my favorite of the Egyption Gods since I first saw in the anime. And the moment I got my first trio set when I was younger, I did my best to build a deck that I thought would work towards Slifer's advantage, leveraging trap monsters to fill the field and some light deck shuffling/drawing power in order to not only draw Slifer, but fill your hand in order to boost it's power.

This is unfortunately, an untested deck, as all my friends stopped playing years ago, so if anyone uses it, I'd love to know how it fairs and how it could be improved.

I left the extra deck & side deck empty, because quite frankly, I have no idea what would synergize best with what's there, if anything at all. My physical E&S decks are just a mishmash of XYZ/Synchros with little to no cohesion with the main deck outside of being full of "powerhouses"
41 card lab deck

Just an idea for now. Ash is a 1 card combo by itself, while WANTED/Diabellstar + Equip-Spell (except Rondo) also works. I first tried playing 2 Populus in case I draw it, but Populus + Ohime/Prep or One For One still works. I rarely drew Populus and most of the time I had Ohime or Prep to discard Jet Synchron. 

Extra Deck and Side Deck are nowhere near optimal and probably the Main Deck could be improved upon as well (non-engine may not be ideal). Bonfire is an option in the Main Deck as well by cutting 1 WANTED + 1/2 more cards or even maybe by cutting the Diabellstar package. For the Extra Deck, at least 2 Herald and 1 Braver is mandatory. 3rd Herald, ASSD, Zeus, Selene, Accesscode, Almiraj, Rank 1s, Rank3s, Downerd can all be at least considered in my opinion. 

Please feel free to give your advice/recommendations.

Normal ze amin, add foxy tune, foxy tune eff discard a card that isnt 1 of the 2 runick spells, special sharakusai, sharakusai eff special rising carp, rising carp eff special wa gon and deer note from deck, wa gon eff add extreme session, make dragon drive, dragon drive cl1 deer note cl2, add madame spider and special back sharakusai, draw 1 card off of extreme session, activate extreme session's other effect banishing foxy tune and special summoning madame spider, activate extreme session's draw 1 eff for the second time, activate a runick spell special hugin, hugin eff pitch any card add fountain, use fountain, make hyper lib.

(Disclaimer: If your opponent has a deck which doesn't contain any monsters in Main Deck, this won't work. Otherwise, you can burn your opponent.)

Welcome! In this deck, we will FTK the opponent with Number 43 alongside Cephalopod. This is really a tricky one, so let's have a look!

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, send Number 13 to GY. Also, send The Legendary Fisherman + Necroface to GY with Ravenous. Then, Special Summon Banisher with Saryuja and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon by banishing Necroface + Formula/Integrator to unlock "Primal Seed" loop.

2) Reach the board state as shown:

  • This is the beginning of "Primal Seed" loop board.

  • This is your ideal board. So, destroy Saryuja and 3 x Main Monster Zones (MMZ) with "Offerings to the Doomed". Then, revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 via "Rank-Up-Magic Launch". Place Number 43 into Extra Monster Zone (EMZ).
  • While at it, don't forget to activate "Chain Summoning". I did it with "Offerings >>> Reload >>> Chain" combination but you can play "Chain Summoning" at anytime prior to this board state, which is up to your imagination.
  • Revive TLF and replace it with TLF III, seen at the center. Next, revive two monsters in a way that you could Synchro Summon Ruddy. I brought forth Ancient + Martial but feel free to revive any duo up to your preferences. No matter what, don't use Chaos/Banisher/TLF III as Synchro material for Ruddy.

3) After fetching "Necroface" with "Primal Seed", you can banish "Necroface" again by playing "Silent Graveyard" and discarding "Necroface". Since Banisher is present, whatever you have discarded will be delivered to BZ anyways. In addition, GY effects for either player will be negated, which will come in handy later on. You can repeat this step until you have completely depleted your opponent's Main Deck.

4) Synchro Summon Ruddy, which can be done by using Ancient + Martial as materials. Activate Ruddy to banish GY of both players. Next, activate TLF III to return your opponent's banished cards to GY...

  • Your opponent can't disturb you with GY effects, which was covered with "Silent Graveyard" in #3.

5) So far, your opponent has lots of monsters in GY while you have none thanks to Ruddy + TLF III shenanigans done in #4. Here, Normal Summon Cephalopod without Tribute to fill the remaining spot. Next, Normal Summon Cephalopod with Tribute, which has to include Cephalopod and anything but Number 43 + Banisher...

  • When you activate Cephalopod, you will deal damage with multiples of 300 with respect to difference of monsters between your opponent and you. Since the damage will be doubled thanks to TLF III, it can be enough to one-shot your opponent.
  • However, that's not at all. You actually gain LP first before dealing some damage. Therefore, after Cephalopod has inflicted the damage, Number 43 will also ask if you want to convert the amount you gained as LP into damage, right back at your opponent.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "The Legendary Fisherman III" can be found within "Rulers of the Deep" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Ruddy Rose Dragon" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Mannadium Trisukta" can be found within "Indomitable Pride" Timed Pack to save 30 SR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 210 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

deck_excerpt: Fire King Snake-Eye Post Phantom Nightmare
deck_description: Fire King Snake-Eye Post Phantom Nightmare
RA

The ritual variant of the Blue-Eyes takes it back to its roots as a beat down deck! Being untargetable makes Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon a formidable foe! Additions to the deck like Dogmatika Punishement add protection and consistency to the strategy

So, have you ever wanted to try out Number 33 FTK, seen in "Side Deck", but couldn't because Number 33 is UR card to craft? What a surprise, I'm on the same boat. Therefore, I would like to do the same but with C103, which is SR card to craft. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) First, place "Zexal Field". Then, Special Summon Yajiro with Saryuja, to the center of battlefield. Otherwise, Yajiro will destroy itself.

2) If your opponent's side is full, clear with "Raigeki". Otherwise, give Yajiro to opposing side with "Shien's Spy". Place Yajiro at where it can jump back and forth to adjacent Main Monster Zones but also very far away from your monsters.

3) Set "Waking the Dragon" to where Yajiro can bounce. Then, Special Summon only one monster...

  • If Panda has charges, use it to Special Summon Level 1 dude at where Waking is.
  • If Shamisen is in your GY, use its ability to Special Summon at where Waking is.
  • If Panda/Shamisen are out of order, Special Summon Ghost or Tricky to where they will be safe from Yajiro while destroying Waking in the process.

4) Yajiro has destroyed Waking. That means you can cheat out C1000. Place C1000 to where Yajiro can pop it and don't forget to activate "Zexal Field" and attach Dugares into C1000.

5) Yajiro has destroyed C1000. That means you can cheat out IC1000. Place IC1000 to where IC1000 and Yajiro look at each other and replace Yajiro with IC1000 by playing "Mystic Box".

6) Special Summon Ghost and Tricky with their abilites. Next, XYZ Summon C103 by using Librarian + Ghost + Tricky as materials. Then, activate C103 and target IC1000 to deal 100k damage to your opponent for the FTK...

  • Even if you have used Number 33, it will be no different other than using 2 x Level 5 monsters as XYZ materials instead of 3 x Level 5 monsters.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" + "Zexal Field" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Raigeki" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Sacred Sword of Seven Stars" can be found within "Celestial Dragon and Bear" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60" + "Number C1000" + "Number IC1000" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number C103: Ragnafinity" can be found within "Sword of the Seventh One" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Mannadium Trisukta" can be found within "Indomitable Pride" Timed Pack to save 30 SR! Don't miss out before it's too late!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

This is the VV build that I've had the most success with in tourneys. The ratios are very simple:

Your 6 1 card starters in:

3x Novox (Lo)

3x Diviner

Your other starters in:

3x Saffira

3x Barrier

3x Pre-Prep

Your ritual mons and spells in:

2x Skull Guardian

2x Sauravis

2x Prayer

Your miscellaneous combo pieces:

1x Old man Sauravis

1x Trias Hierarchia

1x Radiance of the Voiceless Voice

 

Finally, your 14 ht:

3x Nibiru: Not only is it a high impact ht in the upcoming meta, it's also a LIGHT that's over Level 7 meeting the requirements for a Ritual Summon. Also it Tributing means excellent synergy with Diviner in the scenarios where your hand is Diviner and ht and Diviner gets stopped.

3x Droll: Another high-impact ht in the upcoming meta.

3x Veiler: Very underrated ht as at times it can end even a FK Snake Eye player turn, but the most important part is it's a LIGHT and not HOPT.

3x Imperm: Imperm is just extremely versatile, not HOPT, and can be topdecked. Doesn't play into Talents/Thrust either.

2x Ash: Ash is honestly such a bad ht in the upcoming meta, because if FK has any way to get an extender, your Ash is helping them more than huritng. Still Ash is too generic and strong against decks like Branded and Labs to just cut entirely. Ash paired with another ht can be effective against FK as well. That's why I choose to play it at 2.

41 cards just makes side decking much easier and it doesn't actually reduce the consistency much. Plus you slightly lower chance of seeing bricks.

deck_excerpt: A good deck guide for the upcoming archetype Voiceless Voice.
deck_description:
Hello fellow duelists.

 

Welcome back to another deck guide for the new archetype Voiceless Voice.

Voiceless Voice is my favorite deck this format and im pretty sure that it will get some good placements in the TCG too like in the OCG.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

First what is Voiceless Voice?

The first cards what were introduced in our cardgame where in Novox's Prayer & Skull Guardian in the Tournament Pack 2.

Now Konami started to extend these two cards to a solid and very consistent archetype in 2024.

So let's hop in to the guide.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Maindeck cards:

At first we will start with the maindeck cards i will not talk about the Handtraps because i hope that everyone knows what Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Droll & Lock Bird , Called by the Grave  & Infinite Impermanence  does.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Archetype specific cards:

Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple


- main starter

- on normal or special summon place 1 "Voiceless Voice" Continous Spell/Trap from your deck face up               in your   S/T zone

- can be used as the entire ritual summon material for a LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster

- if a LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster is special summoned

  to your field while this card is in your GY special summon it

- always 3 copies

 

You always want to a Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple in your starthand or another monster what we are taking a look on later.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Saffira, the Wise Voiceless Voice Queen 

 

 

- main combo piece

- discard this card and send 1 ritual spell from your deck to your GY then add 1 LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster from the deck to your hand

- banish this card from your graveyard to ritual summon 1 LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster from your hand by tributing monsters from your hand or field whose total levels equal or exceed the lelvel of the ritual monster.

- always 3 copies

 

You mainly search saffira from the effect of Voiceless Voice Barrier but we come to this later.

 

 

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Sauravis, the Sagely Voiceless Voice Dragon 

 

- extender

- spell recycler

- you can special summon this card by shuffling 2 spells from your hand or GY back in to your deck, including

  at least 1 ritual spell

- when your opponent activates a card or effect(Quick Effect) you can return this card to your hand and   special summon 1 LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster from your hand or deck to the field but shuffle it into the deck during the endphase of the next turn

- only 1 copy

 

You only searching sauravis if you have anything in your hand or in the next turn.

 

_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Skull Guardian, the Voiceless Voice Protector 

 

- boss monster

- main beater

- negate & destroy with Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple  on field

- gains 2050 atk while Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple  is on your filed in your GY

- if this card is ritual summoned you can add 1 "Voiceless Voice" monster or 1 dragon ritual monster from

  your deck to your hand.

- 2 copies

With the normal 1 card combo the opponent cannot target any light monster we control with card effects and we have

a negate with Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended  in hand for another negate if they kill our Voiceless Voice Barrier

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Saffira, Queen of Dragons 

 

- supportive boss monster

- tech ritual card

- during the end phase, if this card was ritual summoned this turn or if a LIGHT monster was sent from the hand or

   deck to the GY this turn while this card was face up on the field you can activate 1 of those effects:

- Draw 2 cards, then discard 1 card

- Discard 1 random card from your opponents hand

- add 1 LIGHT monster from your GY to your hand

- i use this only as a spice card i doesn,t come up to often but it's a good suprise for the opponent, its like another

  version of triple tactics talent(when the new  Saffira, Dragon Deity of the Voiceless Voice drops in another

                                                          we  will replace her with the new one but i will write a updated guide for this version)

_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Voiceless Voice Barrier 

 

- one of Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple searchabke cards

- while we control Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple  and a LIGHT ritual monster our opponent's monsters

  can only target Ritual monster for attacks, also your opponent cannot target Light monsters we control with card

  effects

- during main phase we can add 1 "Voiceless Voice" card or 1 "Skull Guardian" ritual monster from deck to our hand

  except Voiceless Voice Barrier 

- definetly 3 copies (one of the best cards in our deck)

 

 

_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Voiceless Voice Prayer 

 

- can be used to ritual summon any LIGHT ritual monster

- if a face up LIGHT ritual monster(s) you control leaves the field by an opponents card effect(exept during the dmg

  step) you can banish this card from your GY; special summon 1 Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended ,

  Saffira, Queen of Dragons or Skull Guardian, the Voiceless Voice Protector  from your hand or deck

 ignoring its summoning conditions

 

- 2 up to 3 copies

 

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Voiceless Voice Authority 

 

- card recycler

- mass detroy card

- shuffle 1 LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monster or 1 ritual spell from your hand or GY into the deck

  and if you do, take 1 "Voiceless Voice" monster from your deck either add it to your hand or special summon it

  (you grab & special sauravis most of the time with it)

- target cards your opponent controls up to the number of LIGHT warrior or dragon ritual monsters you control and

  destroy both them and this card

- 1 up to 3 copies (i normally play 1 its enough for most of the time but i saw some OCG lists playing 3)

 

 

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Other tech cards:

Now we know what all voiceless voice cards do so let's take a closer look on to the tech cards in this deck before we are heading over to the combo lines.

Main deck tech cards:

Diviner of the Herald 

 

Diviner of the Herald is another Starter in this deck.

If we normal summon her we can dump a fairy monster from our deck or extra deck to the GY normally we are  sending Trias Hierarchia to activate the GY effect of Trias Hierarchia and tribute Diviner of the Herald to activate her GY effect to special summon Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple from our deck in defence.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Trias Hierarchia 

 

Trias Hierarchia is 1 of the 2  possible sending pieces for Diviner of the Herald . By sending Trias Hierarchia you can tribute diviner to activate her GY effect for special summoning 1 level 2 or lower fairy type monster from your deck so we are special summon Novox, the Voiceless Voice Disciple .

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Dogmatika Maximus 

 

We are searching Dogmatika Maximus with Nadir Servant by sending 1 monster from the extra deck to the GY.

We are choosing the card we send after the deck we are facing if we dont know what we are facing we are sending Garura, Wings of Resonant Life to draw 1 card.

A good thing is that "Voiceless Voice" doesn't really need the extra deck so we can start to empty out the extra deck by using his effect to send 2 extra deck monster from your extra deck to the GY and your opponent have to send the same amount of cards (2cards) or using him to tribute for the Odd-Eyes Pendulumgraph Dragon which is a spell negate.

 

 

 

 

 

Nadir Servant 

 

This is our searcher for Dogmatika Maximus  from the deck or GY by sending 1 monster from the extra deck to the GY.

Don't forget that you cannot go into Dyna Mondo for example after you activated this spell because you are locked out of extra deck summons.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Pre-Preparation of Rites 

 

This spell card is a your searcher for Voiceless Voice Prayer and after this you can add 1 ritual monster from your deck or gy to your hand whose name is listed on the ritual spell.

This card gives your access to all of your ritual monsters: Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended , Skull Guardian, the Voiceless Voice Protector or Saffira, Queen of Dragons .

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

The last maindeck card we are taking a closer look at is Odd-Eyes Pendulumgraph Dragon 

 

This card gives you some good effects

If this card is your pendulum zone you can give this card back to the hand in the end phase and you can add ritual spell from your deck or GY to your hand.

His monster effect gives you good advantage so if you have him in your monster zone and your opponent activate a spell effect or card you can place him in your pendulum zone and negate this effect after this you can special summon 1 "Odd-Eyes" Monster from your extra deck.

With this effect you want to summon Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon at first for a omni negate and a backshuffle of an opponents card on the field.

 

 

 

 

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

The Extra Deck

The extra deck is our storage for some spicy tech cards. I will provide you a list with all the cards with the effects and some techs to some of the cards.

Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon 

 

We are special summon this card with the effect of Odd-Eyes Pendulumgraph Dragon .

It's our first summoning target with his effect.

After he is on the field we have backshuffle on summon and a omni negate after the activation of a opponents card or effect.

 

 

 

 

 

 

Garura, Wings of Resonant Life 

 

This is mainly our sending target for Nadir Servant or Dogmatika Maximus that

draws you 1 card after discarding to the GY but it's also a good Super Polymerization target.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Elder Entity N'tss 

 

This is mainly our sending target for Nadir Servant or Dogmatika Maximus

that destroys 1 card on the field after discarding to the GY but it's also a Super Polymerization target.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Mudragon of the Swamp 

 

It's a Super Polymerization target

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Odd-Eyes Wing Dragon 

 

This card is our 2nd summon target for Odd-Eyes Pendulumgraph Dragon 

we are using him to give grindgame pressure because when he is in your monster zone you can active th effect to negate a face up monster or to destroy all level 5 or higher monster our opponent controls.

after this card is destroyed you can place him in the pendulum zone and gains the effect to atk boost one for your monsters while it battles

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Golden Cloud Beast - Malong 

 

This is mainly our sending target for Nadir Servant or Dogmatika Maximus

that targets 1 face up card on the opponents field and return it back to the hand.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Herald of the Arc Light 

 

He is a good sending target for Diviner of the Herald 

if he was sent to the GY you can activare his effect to add 1 ritual spell or spell from your deck to the hand.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Deep Sea Prima Donna 

 

This is mainly our sending target for Nadir Servant or Dogmatika Maximus

that give you a back shuffle for a banished card like mostly Saffira, the Wise Voiceless Voice Queen  or Voiceless Voice Prayer 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis 

 

If our opponent special summoned 2 or more monsters from the extra deck in his turn we can special summon

this card to our field by using one monster that you control with the highest ATK as material.

If you do, you cannot Normal or Special Summon monsters for the rest of this turn. While this Xyz Summoned monster

is on the field, neither player can activate the effects of monsters with 3000 or more ATK.

 

 

 

 

 

 

Dyna Mondo 

 

He is a very good card for like every ritual deck what is out there right now

if don't us any Dogmatika spells you can build Dyna Mondo  in your turn to shuffle back a card from your opponents

field by targeting a ritual monster in your GY and a opponents card.

You can Tribute this card, then target 1 Ritual Monster in your GY; either add it to your hand or Special Summon it.

 

 

 

 

 

 

S:P Little Knight 

 

If this card is Link Summoned using a Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, or Link Monster as material: You can target 1 card on the field or in either GY; banish it, also your monsters cannot attack directly this turn.

When your opponent activates a card or effect (Quick Effect): You can target 2 face-up monsters on the field, including a monster you control; banish both until the End Phase.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Linkuriboh 

 

This little guy can be used to trigger the tribute effect of Diviner of the Herald 

it's a also a extra interuption if the opponent tries to attack your monsters to 0 the atk of a monster

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Relinquished Anima 

 

steals a monster from the opponent what is in front of your link arrow and place it in your S/T zone and also gains the ATK from that monster

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

deck_excerpt: Wyrming it all up in here
deck_description:
Yes, I know that Ashened has a Level 9 monster, but as it currently stands, the Deck doesn't do too much as of now. Perhaps the second wave of support can give the Deck more things that they can play with. Right now, the Deck's best card locks you into Pyros and the Level 9's own effect to Summon itself Summons it to your opponent's field. And while I could technically work with that, it's not going to look pretty unless I see what the second wave has to bring. We are looking at Yang Zing today. Yang Zing has 1 Level 9 monster and that is Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing which is a Level 9 LIGHT Wyrm Synchro Monster. It is a generic Synchro Monster, and while you control this Synchro Summoned monster, your opponent cannot activate effects of monsters with the same original Attribute(s) as the Yang Zing monsters used for the Synchro Summon of it. And when Chaofeng is destroyed by battle or card effect and sent to the GY, you can add a Tuner from your Deck to your hand. And as a soft once per turn, when a monster(s) your opponent controls is destroyed by battle or card effect, you can Special Summon 1 Wyrm monster from your Deck in Defense whose original Attribute is the same as the original Attribute of 1 of those destroyed monsters. Now, Chaofeng is a generic Synchro Monster, so you don't really need to go through hoops in Yang Zing combos to get it out, and it is not like we are really utilizing Chaofeng for any of its effects, even though it is a floodgate, because we are not making it with several different Attributed Yang Zing monsters in the first place. But that doesn't mean I don't want to play actual Yang Zing cards to facilitate getting to Chaofeng in the first place. This is not really necessary, but we are gonna be using our Red Resonator Predaplant engine to get to both Denglong, First of the Yang Zing and Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to get the necessary pieces in place to get to both Chaofeng and full Prediction Princess combo. Even though we are using both Denglong and Ib, it's not gonna be like the Crystron Phoenix and Quariongandrax Prediction Princess Deck I made. That required using Ultra Polymerization for Predaplant Ambulomelides because we needed to get a Synchro Tuner and a non-Tuner Synchro on our field or 2 Tuners and at least 1 non-Tuner based on if we were Summoning Phoenix or Quariongandrax. I could've just skipped Denglong and went for Ultra Poly and Ambulo to get a Level 4 Predaplant from Deck to supplement our Level 5 Ib to immediately make Chaofeng, but I felt like doing some justice for the sake of Yang Zing's name and actually playing a lot more Yang Zing cards than just Chaofeng. It's not like all of those cards will be incorporated into our main combo, but if we are able to access them and utilize them, then we definitely shall. Same 2.5-card combo: Red Resonator and Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and a monster to send to GY. Normal Red Resonator, it Summons Scorpio from hand, Scorpio sends a monster from hand to GY to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra triggers to add Ready Fusion from Deck. Synchro Red Resonator and Cobra into Denglong. Denglong adds Yang Zing Path from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon (doesn't have to be, but it is just a suggestion). Denglong sends Zefranui, Secret of the Yang Zing from Deck to GY to make itself a 6. Synchro Denglong and Scorpio for Chaofeng. Denglong triggers in the GY to float into Bi'an, Earth of the Yang Zing from Deck. Pay 1000 to activate Ready Fusion. Ready Fusion gets Allvain the Essence of Vanity from Extra Deck. Synchro Allvain and Bi'an into Ib who searches for World Legacy Monstrosity on Synchro Summon. Activate Monstrosity targeting Chaofeng and you have full Prediction Princess combo once you get Bibliomuse and Deus-X out of the Deck. Before you go to your End Phase, you can activate that Yang Zing Path you searched to shuffle 3 Yang Zings among Denglong, Bi'an, Zefranui, and Chaofeng from your Gy into the Deck to draw 2. The Deck functions really well and it is not bad at all considering that it can have you end on your standard Prediction Princess board or that along with an extra piece of spice. Certainly not bad at all. I'd still much rather prefer something a bit more based like Gate Guardian Prediction Princess. Or maybe something with a better follow-up and recovery play like Coordius Prediction Princess. Or maybe something with a much easier-to-access Level 9 like Runick Prediction Princess. But that is just in my personal opinion. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. For the Main Deck Yang Zings: 2 Zefranui, Secret of the Yang Zing and 1 Bi'an, Earth of the Yang Zing. Don't need to look at their effects since we just need their Levels. Zefranui is the only Level 6 Yang Zing and while you could play Zefraxi, Treasure of the Yang Zing as your Level 3 Yang Zing over Bi'an, Zefraxi is a Pend Monster which means that it goes to the Extra Deck if it leaves the field istead of being sent to the GY. This means that you can't shuffle it from GY into Deck with Yang Zing Path to draw 2. This sounds a like a lot of bull since you are putting 4 Yang Zing monsters into the GY after going through your combo and you only need to shuffle back 3 Yang Zings for Path. But at the same time, what if you want to keep, I don't know, Chaofeng in the GY because you have Succession in hand or are saving it for your following turn for a possible Rank 9 play? 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. On Normal or Special Summon, Scorpio can send a monster from hand to GY to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. Cobra can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from Deck to hand if Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster once per Duel. 2 Lonefire Blossom which can Tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Red Resonator who Special Summons a Level 4 or lower monster from hand on Normal Summon and can target a face-up monster on field and gain LP equal to its ATK on Special Summon. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion and 1 Ready Fusion. Why are we not playing just Instant Fusion? Why do we have to play it and Ready Fusion when your Ready Fusion target can also be Summoned with Instant Fusion? Well, I want to have the option of using 1 or both in case I draw 1 and then search the other. It is similar to how I usually play a copy of World Legacy Succession in addition to my copy of World Legacy Monstrosity. If we draw 1, we can search the other and use both. Instant Fusion is mainly to Special Summon Master of Ham while Ready Fusion is being used to get Allvain the Essence of Vanity. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Yang Zing Path which can target 3 Yang Zing monsters in your GY and shuffle them into the Deck to draw 2 cards. 3 Pot of Prosperity. You might think that Pot and Path clash with each other, and yes, they do. But, Path is not our only Yang Zing search target off of Denglong in the Deck. 3 Resonator Call which searches for a Resonator monster from Deck. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from your hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it but with different names. 1 World Legacy Succession which targets a monster in your GY and Special Summons it to Linkpoint. 1 Nine Pillars of the Yang Zing. It is a Counter Trap that negates a Spell/Trap card or monster effect activation while you control a Yang Zing monster and it shuffles that card back into the Deck and destroys 1 other Yang Zing card you control. This is your other Yang Zing search target for Denglong aside from Path. Think about it: If you draw Instant Fusion or Bibliomuse, you can activate search this off of Denglong instead of path, and when you activate Monstrosity, get Deus-X and Pot of the Forbidden from Deck. And you can use them as material for Aggregator, keeping Chaofeng on the field to ensure that you have a Yang Zing for Nine Pillars. Not only do you get to keep the LIGHT monster effect prevention of Chaofeng, but you also get basically an omni-Counter Trap to protect your field during your opponent's turn. And since Nine Pillars also pops, you can search for Ash Blossom off of Chaofeng too. It's just too good not to play for this interaction.

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment which can be contact fused by banishing 3 monsters you control with different names and it is a Level 9 monster itself. 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Allvain the Essence of Vanity which is a Level 2 Tuner we can access off of the Ready Fusion we will be searching. 1 Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing. 1 Denglong, First of the Yang Zing. It adds a Yang Zing card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon, it can send a Wyrm monster from Deck to GY to change its Level to the Level of the sent monster, and if it leaves the field, it can float into a Yang Zing monster from Deck. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Daniel Guo

Tournament: Brisbane WCQ Regional – January 20th 2024

Placement: Top 8

This is pretty much a water toolbox deck. I wanted to use the new White Fish engine in my water deck, but I couldn't decide between Ice Barrier and Deep Sea for my main engine, so you're gettin' both. DS is next. You can't run both because they each have one key unit that requires a normal summon. Aside from Ice Barrier, I've added pretty much every generic water engine that doesn't clash with your ns. In fact, the only search spell that is hard once per turn is White Reincarnation. If you don't have Sardine in your hand when you activate it, grab Sardine; but if you do, grab Sunfish for a +2 summon and you'll have access to level 8 synchros.

We should all know at this point that Icejade Ran Aegirine is a free Gymir Aegirine, and since Cradle's only restriction is based on the Icejades you already have out, you could play all three Cradles and get all 3 Rans. That's obviously sub-par because you'd want Tremora or Kingfisher for your third copy, but since you only need to proc Ran once, getting another copy for her discard fodder is more efficient than losing your other hand effects.

The Ice Barriers have a LOT of versatility in this deck. Thanks to the new Mirror Magic Master (henceforth MMM), a level 2 Aqua, two Toadally Awesomes looks like an achievable play once again! The IBs that require others to summon are limited to 2. I don't wanna be relying on 3-ofs that need another card to get out. This specific set of IBs have a lot of ways of bouncing each other around. Revealer gets you MMM or Hexa, Hexa sends MMM to gy which gets you any IB monster, Speaker and Prior are free with another IB on field, and Prior can trade himself for any other IB in the gy. It's worth noting that if you didn't special summon Prior with his effect, you are still free to summon level 5+. And summoning Archethys with MMM's tokens = profit, but you'll be locked to water synchros afterward. There are 5 different lvl 4 monsters in this deck, 4 of which you can get out for free. Any two of them can build Bahamut Shark, which nets you that second Toad. And of course, Swap Frog. You have to hard draw into it, but in a deck that is basically 39 water monsters (9 of the spells search for one), you should always be able to ss it.

deck_excerpt: Transaction Rollback is the second coming of SCYTHE LOCK AKA V.F.D AKA VERY FUN DRAGON AKA TRUE KING OF ALL CALAMITIES!
deck_description:
Are you ready for the second coming of SCYTHE LOCK AKA V.F.D AKA VERY FUN DRAGON AKA TRUE KING OF ALL CALAMITIES? 
 
Well, with the new card from MZMI Transaction Rollback combined with Ghost Meets Girl - A Masterful Mayakashi Shiranui Saga, you can effectively skip your opponent's turn! No more special summoning except from the GY or banished pile! Transaction Rollback copies any normal trap card's effect in the GY for the cheap cost of half of your lifepoints, and Ghost Meets Girl's effect stops any summon from the hand, deck or extra deck! 
 
How do we get these cards in the GY? You either mill them with your various milling options available in Tearlaments, or you can summon Beatrice! Beatrice mills ANY card from deck as a quick effect, so you can easily grab your T-Rollback + Ghost Meets Girl set-up with just two level 6 monsters. This version of Tearlaments is specifically optimized to get you there!
 
Once you resolve T-Rollback (which is extremely easy in this deck), your win is a hop skip and a jump away into OTK next turn! This "cheap" strategy feels like Scythe Lock or Calamity Lock all over again, and that's because it is! The simple access of an Extra Deck monster (Beatrice) leads to a turn skip that is nearly impossible to stop! Let's abuse this strategy for cheap wins before Beatrice gets banned!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

Forming the core of this strategy, the Tearlament portion of this deck consists of 18 cards. 3 Perlereino allow you to search for the 9 maindeck Tearlament monsters: Scheiren, Havnis, Merrli, 3 Reinoheart and 3 Tearlaments Kashtira. 2 Scream, 2 Sulliek, and 1 Metanoise search/recur for additional cards when milled. 

 

A HORUS package is used mainly for turboing out Zombie Vampire for mills and is composed of 6 cards - 3 Imsety, 1 Hapi, and 2 King's Sarcophagus. 

 

A HERO package is used, composed of 2 Malicious and 1 Denier to enable easy summons of level 6s so that Beatrice can be made. In the Extra Deck, Destiny Hero Dangerous can be fused with any Tearlaments + Destiny Hero and with a discard, that Dangerous by himself forms Beatrice.

 

A KASHTIRA package of 2 Fenrir and 3 Kashtira Tearlaments are used. Fenrir is simultaneously a combo piece (since it searches for Tear Kash) and a boardbreaker, but only two are used in this deck, since they don't really do anything when milled.

 

A SHADDOLL package is included to provided extra milling power (Helshaddoll Hollow) and card advantage (Shaddoll Beast). 

 

Finally, the new win condition, TRANSACTION ROLLBACK with its target, GHOST MEETS GIRL are included. Two Foolish Burial Goods are also included for extra consistency and access.

 

You may have noticed that there are hardly any handtraps or generic staples in this deck. The theory behind this build of Tearlaments is that it has so much gas that it can play through all of your opponent's interruptions just fine, as long as your graveyard is accessible and you aren't floodgated to death.

 

40 cards are used to ensure this strategy is as consistent and compact as possible. In addition to bricking less, the mills will have much better results than bigger Tearlaments variants because of the deck's compact size. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger graveyard effects. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos. 

 

There are no straightforward "combos" for Tearlaments due to the random nature of the deck. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is considered as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their main deck. 

 

What differentiates this version of Tearlaments from the others is its "instant win button" in the form of Transaction Rollback combined with Ghost Meets Girl. On top of having to deal with all your Tearlament centred interruptions, your opponent will have to deal with a summon lock as well! This essentially spells defeat for your opponent since it's typically an unsalvageable situation for most strategies. For this win condition to be available, both Transaction Rollback and Ghost Meets Girl need to be in the GY, and that can be accomplished by your random mills or by summoning Beatrice. Beatrice setting up this turn skip win con by herself essentially makes her the second coming of True King of All Calamities! XYZ monster -> INSTANT WIN BUTTON!

 

The level 6s in this deck to summon Beatrice are Garura, Malicious, Dangerous and Shyama. Garura is summoned by fusing two Tearlament girls (it also grants an additional draw when detached from Beatrice).  Malicious can be summoned from deck if he is milled. Fusing into Dangerous can also summon Malicious from deck, which allows Beatrice to be made. Shyama can be summoned if milled, and if you set a card to be destroyed so it can summon itself to the field (Also it triggers your Tearlament spell/trap effects!) 

 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Remember, two level 6s -> Beatrice -> opponent's turn is skipped. Try as much as possible to get his set up, since that means you basically win the game!
  • When forced to go second, you can side out your T-Rollback cards, Shyama, Destrudo, Destiny Hero cards and Shaddoll cards for more blind second cards. 
  • If you need to get a card out of your hand, Barricade Borgblocker is the perfect card for the job. Also, if you have Shyama in the GY you can set your spell/trap and Shyama can destroy it. A nice bonus with Shyama is that it triggers your Tearlament spells/traps so they can search. 
  • Since Droll is such a common card this format, try to search first with cards that get you a really valuable combo piece. For example, I would activate Imsety first to search for King's Sarcophagus over something minor like Terraforming -> Perlereino.
  • Horus cards are incredible at cracking established boards and can out powerful boss monsters that have negates. 
  • Another card you can use for Transaction Rollback is Eradicator Epidemic Virus to wipe out your opponent's entire hand of spells and traps. There are other targets for T-Rollback. Experiment and discover crazier ways to abuse the card!
  • Any Tearlaments strategy is infamous for requiring a great deal of skill to pilot, since the duelists is required to know all the various interactions that goes on in the GY, and to remember how many cards are left in their deck - the while considering how the opponent will react to the plays. This deck is not easy, so practice makes perfect with Tearlaments. 
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 
Not gonna lie, this deck's wins feels extremely toxic and stupidly cheap! Why is Beatrice legal??? Why are turnskips that are normally very hard to access easily accessible??? 
 
On top of all the powerful Tearlaments gameplay, a special summon lock with Transaction Rollback renders it impossible for your opponent to even interact! This FTK is consistent due to Beatrice, a card already often made in the strategy. Sometimes, the natural milling that Tearlaments already does creates this set-up as you combo along!
 

IMO Transaction Rollback is such a ridiculous and stupidly strong card, and Tearlaments is the perfect strategy to abuse this playstyle. I'm personally hoping I don't face any Transaction Rollback decks in the near future, because it's a real pain to duel against.

 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_description: Have fun figuring out how to play this deck cuz even I barely understand what to do X_X

Note:

- If you play second and Opp has a negate board, consider Surrender early.

- If Diviner or any Drytron gets Ash (and you don't have the piece to be added at hand), then just Surrender.

- To add Consistency, I don't play any Ash or Maxx C or Called by. Instead, I added

+ 1 Foolish Burial to search Drytron faster,

+1 Dark Factory in case we mess up,

+2 or 3 Preparation of Rites to add Benten/Idaten + recycle Meteonis

+2 Miracle Fusion because sometimes Curious can betray us.

+ 1 or 2 any level-1 Normal Fairy because otherwise, we auto lose if one of the Exodia's pieces in the opening hand (so Advanced Ritual Art cannot be activated)

+You can replace Monster Reborn with Red Reboot or Called by.

 

Opening with: Alpha Thuban + Zeta Aldhibah and you dont have any Cyber Angel girls.

 

Stage 1: Board set up

1. Tribute Zeta - summon Alpha - add Benten

2. Tribute Benten - summon Zeta - Benten adds Diviner, Zeta adds Meteonis Drytron

3. Normal summon Diviner, send Herald of Arc Light (Diviner becomes level 6), add Batosbuster (do not add Idaten, because you will lose)

4. XYZ summon Fafnir with 2 materials to the Extra Monster Zone, send Gamma.

5. Activate Meteonis in hand, Ritual summon Benten with Fafnir's Material.

6. Activate Meteonis in the Grave, minus 1000 ATK from Fafnir, add Meteonis back to the hand.

7. Use Gamma's effect, tribute Benten on the field and Summon 1 Drytron from the Grave, Benten adds Idaten.

8. Activate Meteonis in hand (again), Ritual summon Idaten with Fafnir's final Material, Idaten adds Advanced Ritual Art. Now, your hand should have 1 Batobuster, 1 Advanced Ritual Art, and full 6 monsters on the field (Diviner, Idaten, Beatrice, Fafnir, Gamma + 1 Drytron)

 

Stage 2: Dump Exodia

9. Use Diviner and Idaten, XYZ Summon Beatrice, then use her effect to send the Head (Exodia the Forbidden One) to the grave.

10. Use Advanced Ritual Art, Ritual summon Batobuster, by dumping all other Exodia parts from the deck (2 Legs and 2 Arms). Batobuster on summon add to the hand Mafteal.

11. Activate Mafteal's effect right away (if you forget, you will lose the ability to normal summon again)

 

Stage 3: Link up and add back Exodia.

 

12. Use Fafnir and Batobuster, link summon into Space Insulator (or Pentestag)

13. Summon Mafteal. Mafteal summons Batobuster again. (dont summon Batobuster into the zone you are going to Link summon next)

14. Use Mafteal, Beatrice and Gamma, link into Curious. Curious sends the trap Backup Soldier and then mill 3 cards. If you don't play 2 Miracle Fusion, this is where thing might go wrong.

15. Use Curious and Batobuster, link into Firewall Dragon (Do not activate Firewall yet). Now, Pentestag (or Space Insulator) is co-linking with Firewall.

16. Use the final Drytron, link summon to Linkuriboh (put it on the left side of Firewall), then link again to Secure Gardna. Now Firewall is co-link 2. If you don't have another Drytron on the field, you can use Monster Reborn.

17. Activate Firewall, add the Head and 1 of the Leg/Arm. There are 3 more in the grave waiting to be collected.

18. Use Firewall and Pentestag, link summon into Anaconda.

19. Activate Anaconda, sacrifice 2000 LP, send and copy the effect of Miracle Synchro Fusion, banish any link/synchro/xyz in the grave to summon Coordius.

20. Activate Coordius, sacrifice 2000 LP, add Backup Soldier from the grave to the hand.

21. Set Backup Soldier. End your turn. When opp draw their first card, activate Backup Soldier and add the rest of the 3 pieces of Exodia to the hand.

22. Victory.

deck_description:
I know this has been done already, but I wanted to make it for myself. Obviously Raika (Calamity Seed) is a huge Traptrix engine, and unlike Rikka, Traptrix knows how to share the sandbox with the other types. Only Arachnocampa will lock you into Insect/Plant monsters, but only from the extra deck, meaning that main deck lizard is still free to summon. Thanks to Atypus' recipe, the Raika link-2 is a free Atypus. I only put 2 beetle and lizard because they need other cards out to summon. The idea is to search both with seed's effect (the "seed" seed), banish lizard, then bottom deck lizard to summon beetle and start link climbing. Raika is a very automatic play style.

Do I honestly need to write a tutorial on Traptrix at this point? I just sided some traps I didn't find immediately useful in the deck, but they could still have valuable applications. I just wanted to keep the extra deck pure (and cheap), but if you have better cards you wanna run, like Benghalancer the Resurgent, go for it. Keep Rafflesia at 2 (and maybe even bump her up to 3) so you can stack those deck traps.
